<HEADLINE> Southwest China Province Striving to Develop Education </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, January 4 (Xinhua) -- Southwest China's Yunnan
Province, which is inhabited by 26 ethnic groups, has made rapid
progress in developing its local education.
</P>
<P>
At present, 90 out of the 127 counties and cities in Yunnan
have implemented the six-year compulsory education, and the
nine-year compulsory education has been introduced to the
province's 34 counties and cities.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that 98.63 percent of of the province's primary
school-age children are now in school, and 76.5 percent of the
primary school graduates entered middle schools in 1997, showing
increases of 0.52 and 1.45 percentage points over the previous
year.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, some 490,000 young people in the province shook off
illiteracy in 1997, with a ratio of illiteracy going down to 14
percent from the former 20 percent during the Eighth Five-Year
Plan (1991-1995) period.
</P>
<P>
To meet the requirements of social and economic growth, the
province emphasized the growth of vocational education with the
total enrolment in vocational schools standing at 39,800 and the
number of their students reaching 112,100 last year.
</P>
<P>
The province also scored marked progress in the training of
college students and postgraduates and in adult education.
</P>
<P>
The province's input in education amounted to 5 billion yuan
(600 million US dollars) last year as against 4.13 billion yuan
(498 million US dollars) in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
