<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-04 16:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Levy-2ndadd: Netanyahu Regrets Over Levy's Resignation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 4 (Xinhua)-- Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu has expressed regret over resignation of his Foreign
Minister David Levy.
</P>
<P>
According to a statement broadcast by local radio this evening,
Netanyahu hoped Levy would reconsider his decision to leave the
government.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy announce Sunday in Tel
Aviv his resignation from the government led by Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu, creating a political crisis in the country.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press conference, Levy said he will send his
resignation letter to Netanyahu right after the announcement.
</P>
<P>
Levy said he made this decision after serious considerations
and he is no longer a cabinet member after sending his resignation
letter to Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
Giving his reasons for resignation, Levy said the proposed
1998 state budget does not address the country's social and
economic problems, particularly the sufferings of the low income
families and these people really needed for support.
</P>
<P>
He criticized the government for ignoring the promises made
to him last Summer in formulating the the state budget and
for lacking the positive intention in moving the Middle East
peace process forward.
</P>
<P>
In his agreement reached last Summer with the government,
Netanyahu promised to allocate about 100 million U.S. dollars as
special budget for Levy's Gesher (bridge) Party to address the
problems of development towns and underprivileged neighborhoods
in the 1998 state budget.
</P>
<P>
Levy also said that another reason for his resignation is that
many cabinet members did not support his policy of resuming peace
talks with the Palestinians, particularly the implementation of
the Hebron Agreement with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Under the law, Levy's resignation would come into effect 48
hours after his resignation letter to the prime minister. So the
prime minister still has two days to persuade him to change his
mind. But it seems that Levy would be unlikely to go back as he
had made very harsh criticisms of the government.
</P>
<P>
With the resignation of Levy from the government, Netanyahu
only enjoys a marginal majority of 61 seats in the 120-member
parliament. Levy's Gesher Party has five seats in the
parliament in which Netanyahu has escaped narrowly several
no-confidence motions in the past several months.
</P>
<P>
The main opposition the Labor Party has already announced that
it would make another no-confidence motion in the parliament
against Netanyahu next week. If the Labor succeeds in winning the
motion, elections would be held within two months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
