<HEADLINE> Iraqi Kurdish Rival Parties Seek Reconciliation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, January 4 (Xinhua) -- Iraq's Patriotic Union of
Kurdistan (PUK) is expecting a positive reply to its peace
call from its rival Kurdistan Democratic Party (KDP), Turkey's
Anatolia News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
The agency quoted a PUK statement as saying that PUK leader
Jalal Talabani sent a letter to KDP Chairman Massoud Barzani
Thursday, seeking a broad reconciliation in a bid to set up a
permanent peace in northern Iraq, but had so far received no
answer from the KDP leader.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that Talabani expressed his hope that
Barzani will give a "positive reply" for the future and freedom
of the Kurdish people in the region.
</P>
<P>
In the letter to Barzani, Talabani also proposed a high-level
meeting between the two factions to sort out their disputes.
</P>
<P>
The two groups agreed on their latest ceasefire in November
after Talabani's forces attacked KDP positions.
</P>
<P>
The two contenders have been fighting for the control of
northern Iraq after the 1991 Gulf War when the Iraqi government
was rendered ineffective by the U.S.-led allied forces to exert
influence there. 
</P>
</TEXT>
