<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Breeding Chinese Fish to Control Water </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, January 4 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe is breeding a Chinese
fish species for the purpose of curbing the weed menace at
Harare's main water supply source, Lake Chivero, some 40
Kilometers outside the capital.
</P>
<P>
Troubled for years by the water weed, particularly the
Hyacinth, authorities at Lake Chivero have tried many ways to
save the water body from choking without much success.
</P>
<P>
On-going experiments have proved that the Grass-Cup fish would
be effective in controlling the weed as the laboratory pond is
free from grass, the Zimbabwe News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
Manyame Fishing Cooperative Chairman Millias Chimutu today
said the fish eats up all sorts of weed, but has to be strictly
controlled as it could grow into a menace itself.
</P>
<P>
An official of the national parks said controlled breeding is
being done in a laboratory and periodic checks would be done to
ensure numbers do not exceed a certain limit.
</P>
<P>
''If we allow the fish to breed more than we can control it
can upset ecology in the lake and we will be very careful,'' he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
