<DOCNO> XIE19980105.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU May Complete Enlargement Negotiation by 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 4 (Xinhua) -- British Foreign Secretary Robin
Cook said today negotiations between the European Union (EU) and
central European countries which have applied for the membership
may be completed by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
However, the talks would be more difficult than those which led
to Austria, Sweden and Finland joining the EU in 1995, Cook told
BBC television in an interview. It took three years for the three
countries to complete negotiation on the membership.
</P>
<P>
"Those were prosperous countries, small countries, all of them
net contributors (to the EU budget)," Cook said.
</P>
<P>
"It is going to take at least that timescale to bring in the
larger countries of central Europe who are of course poorer and
raise particular difficulties for the European budget because of
it," he said.
</P>
<P>
A 15-member EU summit meeting in Luxembourg last month invited
Hungary, Poland, the Czech Republic, Estonia, Slovenia and Cyprus
to begin negotiations on joining the union.
</P>
<P>
The foreign secretary also said his country wanted to set a
"people's agenda" for Europe during its sin-month presidency of
the European Union.
</P>
<P>
Britain wanted to "tackle issues that worry people -- jobs,
crime and the environment -- and show Europe can be part of the
solution to the problem," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
