<HEADLINE> Arafat Welcomes US Peace Efforts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 4 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) President Yasser Arafat today expressed welcome to
the U.S. efforts in moving the Middle East peace process forward,
the Jerusalem Media and Communication Center (JMCC) reported,
</P>
<P>
Arafat, who presided over the PNA cabinet meeting in Jericho,
an self-rule city in the West Bank, said that he was delighted
that the U.S. government decided to send its Middle East peace
envoy Dennis Ross to the region at such a critical time, adding
that he will discuss with Ross problems the peace process faces
next week when they meet.
</P>
<P>
JMCC, an East Jerusalem-based Palestinian news center, also
quoted Arafat as saying that he will travel to Washington on
January 22 to hold talks with U.S. President Bill Clinton on the
Middle East peace process, particularly the issues concerning the
Israeli second troop's redeployment in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
During the Washington talks, he will explain in detail to the
U.S. Administration about the PNA's stand relating to the Israeli
redeployment.
</P>
<P>
Nabil Sha'ath, PNA Planning and International Cooperation
Minister, told a press conference in Jericho today that maps
prepared by Israel about the redeployment could pose serious
dangers to the security of the PNA and the neighboring Arab
states, because Israel's intention of protecting Jordanians from
a Palestinian state is an attempt to damage the relations between
the Jordanian and Palestinian peoples.
</P>
<P>
According the redeployment plan proposed by Israeli National
Infrastructure Minister Ariel Sharon, a 20-kilometer-wide security
zone must be set up in the Jordan River Valley, separating the PNA
and Jordan.
</P>
<P>
Sha'ath strongly denounced this plan, saying it is like a knife
being put onto the back of the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Dennis Ross has reportedly postponed his visit to Israel and
the Palestinian self-rule area from Monday to Tuesday at the
request of Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu due to
political crisis in the Israeli government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
