<DOCNO> XIE19980105.0022 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Profile: Moi Declared Re-Elected as Kenyan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 4 (Xinhua) -- The Electoral Commission (EC)
of Kenya declared today that incumbent President Daniel arap Moi
has won his final five-year term in the just concluded general
elections.
</P>
<P>
The president elect will be sworn in here tomorrow morning.
</P>
<P>
Official results based on 201 out of Kenya's 210
constituencies showed that so far Moi has garnered 2.446 million
votes (40.12 percent), followed by Democratic Party (DP) Chairman
Mwai Kibaki with 1.896 million votes (31.09 percent). National
Development Party leader Raila Odinga took the third place with
only 665,725 votes.
</P>
<P>
The 73-year-old Moi who has been in power since 1978, has also
managed to win 69.38 percent of the votes in Rift Valley
Province, 73.08 in North Eastern Province, 44.67 in Western,
61.05 in Coast, 35.87 in Eastern, 23.52 in Nyanza, 20.56 in
Nairobi and 5.59 in Central Province.
</P>
<P>
Moi holds the record as the longest serving president, vice
president and member of parliament in the history of Kenya.
</P>
<P>
"Moi is like a giraffe, while others are like ordinary small
animals. When they are busy grazing down there, the giraffe is
seeing very far," said late opposition FORD-Kenya Chairman
Jaramogi Odinga.
</P>
<P>
"Moi is a person who can stand on a tight rope, juggle with 20
balls and still manage a smile when the pressure is on," the
Kenya Times newspaper quoted an authoritative international
magazine as saying.
</P>
<P>
Also described by the western press, Moi is the last of
Africa's "Big Men" who believe that Africans have always had
their own way of dealing with issues and need no advice from
abroad.
</P>
<P>
"Moi has made his own footprints in the sands of time," said
former British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher during her visit
to Kenya in January, 1988.
</P>
<P>
He is also seen as a prominent peace-broker and active
regional cooperation advocate in the Great Lakes region and
eastern Africa --with his famous Nyato philosophy -- peace, love
and unity.
</P>
<P>
A member of the Tugen sub-group of the minority Kalenjin
ethnic confederation, Moi was born to the first wife of Kimoi
Chebi on September 2, 1924 in Kurieng'ewo village, Sacho, Baringo
district in Rift Valley Province.
</P>
<P>
He was the fourth and last child and named Toroitich. After
two years of his birth, his father passed away. Moi was brought
up by his mother and one of the elder brothers.
</P>
<P>
At 10, he walked some 28 miles (45 kilometers) every day to
reach Kabartonjo Africa Inland Mission School, and, after the
long walk home, he helped his mother tend the cattle and goats
daily.
</P>
<P>
It was in Kabartonjo that in October 1936, shortly before he
changed schools, Toroitich was baptized into Daniel as a
Christian.
</P>
<P>
First he transferred to another African Inland Mission School
at Kapsabet in 1938 and later to the Government African School,
Kapsabet, where he was the School Football Team Captain.
</P>
<P>
In 1939, Moi took up his first salaried job when he was hired
to drive two head of cattle from Kabarnet to Kapsowar, some 75
miles away. The pay was 2.50 Shillings. "I used it to buy a
Bible," Moi recalled.
</P>
<P>
In 1945, he went to the nearby Kapsabet Teachers Training
College after which he was posted to Kabarnet Intermediate School
as a teacher and became headmaster there in 1948.
</P>
<P>
Moi made his political debut in October, 1955 at the age of 31
when he was nominated as a member of the Legislative Council
which then only included five Africans.
</P>
<P>
The opposition Kenya African Democratic Union (KADU) party was
formed in 1960 and Moi became chairman.
</P>
<P>
He was appointed Education Minister in the pre-independence
coalition government of 1960/61.
</P>
<P>
When KADU was dissolved in 1964 following a merger with the
Kenya African National Union (KANU) led by late President Jomo
Kenyatta, Moi was appointed Home Affairs Minister.
</P>
<P>
Since January 1967 when he was appointed as Kenyatta's vice
president, he had became almost colorless member of the cabinet
who rarely "put a foot wrong," and operated in the deep shadow of
the larger-than-life Kenyatta until August 1978 when Kenyatta
died in Mombasa.
</P>
<P>
Moi succeeded to the presidency peacefully with vows that he
would follow in Kenyatta's footsteps. As an astute chess master
in politics, he included his political foes in his cabinet and
thus quelled their hostility toward him as he built a solid base.
</P>
<P>
In 1982, an attempted coup led by Kenya Air Force officers was
crushed by forces loyal to Moi in just three hours.
</P>
<P>
Moi bowed reluctantly to pressure from donors and opposition
groups and introduced multi-party politics in 1991, but bitterly
blaming it for what he perceives to be an upsurge in tribalism,
violence and other social evils.
</P>
<P>
However, he won the first democratic multi-party elections in
December 1992 with 36.8 percent of the vote against seven rivals.
</P>
<P>
Moi is a regular church-goer and is said to start his working
day as early as five in the morning every day.
</P>
<P>
Father of two girls and five boys, he divorced his wife in
1976 and has not remarried. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980105.0023 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-04 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Criticizes Jordan for Observing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, January 4 (Xinhua) -- Iran today criticized Jordan for
its decision to send observers to the forthcoming Israeli-Turkish
maneuvers in the Mediterranean, Tehran radio reported.
</P>
<P>
Iranian Foreign Ministry spokesman Mahmoud Mohammadi said that
Israel wanted to regionalize its expansionist policies through the
military cooperations with regional countries.
</P>
<P>
Jordan made the decision to observe the Israeli-Turkish
military exercises in the Mediterranean at a time when most Muslim
countries announced their opposition to the joint maneuvers, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman noted that the Islamic Republic of Iran
expressed its unpleasantness towards the decision of the Jordanian
government and believed that the joint maneuvers would fail to
achieve the objectives.
</P>
<P>
The tripartite military exercises of Israel, Turkey and the
U.S. is scheduled to be held in the eastern Mediterranean on
January 5-9 in accordance to a military cooperation accord signed
between Israel and Turkey in February, 1996.
</P>
<P>
Iran and most Arab countries have expressed great concern
over the military cooperation between Israel and Turkey and the
Eighth Islamic Summit held here last month adopted a resolution
calling for reconsideration of military cooperation between
Islamic countries and Israel.
</P>
<P>
Jordan's recent decision to take part in the maneuvers as an
observer has drawn strong attacks from the Islamic countries,
particularly its neighbors such as Syria.
</P>
<P>
They believed that Jordan's move would help Israel to continue
its aggressions against Arab and Islamic countries and the peace
in the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
