<HEADLINE> Head of French Liberal Democratic Party Rules Out </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, January 4 (Xinhua) -- Alain Madelin, the president of
Liberal Democratic Party, a splinter party from the Gaullist PRP,
said Sunday that his party will not ally with the extreme-right
National Front (FN) in the regional elections in March.
</P>
<P>
"There will not be agreement on the table or under the table
with the National Front," said Madelin, who was finance minister
under the former government of Edouard Balladur, in a television
interview.
</P>
<P>
He also said that one should "fight one by one the ideas of
the National Front in a calm and tranquil way" and not "yield to
an anti-FN hysteria."
</P>
<P>
He suggested addressing the supporters of FN "with the weapon
of reason" during the regional elections.
</P>
<P>
Madelin also linked the adoption by France of the Amsterdam
treaty with the issue of controlling immigration, as France is
preparing for a constitutional amendment in order to sign the
Amsterdam treaty which predicts an enlarged European integration
in political, social and economic fields.
</P>
<P>
Some French political groups have called for a referendum on
the Amsterdam treaty, as they argue that the treaty concerns the
sovereignty of France in the field of immigration, border and
asylum.
</P>
<P>
"If the government wants that we move forward constitutionally
toward the Amsterdam treaty, it should reverse the Chevenement law
on immigration," he said.
</P>
<P>
The new liberal immigration law presented by Interior Minister
Jean-Pierre Chevenement and adopted by the left-dominated National
Assembly last month has met with strong opposition from the
rightwing parties.
</P>
<P>
However, Madelin judged it unnecessary to hold a referendum on
Amsterdam treaty prior to a constitutional amendment, because he
said it is not "a fundamental point" like the adoption of the
Maastricht treaty by France in 1992.
</P>
<P>
President Francois Mitterrand organized a referendum on
Maastricht treaty in September 1992. A weak majority of 51 percent
of the French voters supported it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
