<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-04 18:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Levy-Writethru: Levy's Resignation Deals Fatal Blow to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 4 (Xinhua) -- The days of the Israeli
government led by Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu might be
numbered following today's dramatic resignation of Foreign Minister
David Levy.
</P>
<P>
Levy, Netanyahu's long-time leading political rival who has
threatened to leave the government for six times since
mid-1996, made it clear today that he was no longer crying
wolf this time.
</P>
<P>
Although technically, Netanyahu still has 48 hours to
persuade Levy to change his mind, Levy said his decision was
final, thus shutting the door tight for possible reversal of
his action.
</P>
<P>
He cited two reasons for his decision: the government's
violation of social principles by ignoring the plight of
increasing number of the poor and underpreviliged, and its
inaction to push forward the peace process according to the
signed peace accords.
</P>
<P>
Levy's resignation culminated the current crisis triggered by
the stormy debate and inner wrangling within the coalition over
the proposed 1998 budget, which includes massive cuts in public
welfare expenditure. Levy's Gesher Party has been lobbying for
support among the poor population in order to increase its
political clout.
</P>
<P>
The burst of Levy's anger toward Netanyahu came after he
found out that he was largely ignored by the prime minister
who was preoccupied with wooing several influential religious
parties within the coalition by promising fat deals.
</P>
<P>
While it is still too early to pronounce the end of
Netanyahu government at the time, politicians and analysts
believed this is the beginning. In the absence of the Gesher,
which has five seats in the 120-member Knesset (Parliament), the
coalition's majority will be reduced down to the minimal 61
votes needed to keep going.
</P>
<P>
At present, even if Netanyahu fails to keep Levy within
his government, he could still get the budget passed during
the scheduled Monday vote in the Knesset because he has
secured the two votes of the rightist Moledet Party in the
opposition.
</P>
<P>
The only problem is whether the three hardline members from
Netanyahu's Likud Party, Zeev Begin, Uzi Landau and Reuven
Rivlin, will cross the party line in order to pressure
Netanyahu to be tougher on deciding the pending troop
redeployment in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
But even Netanyahu survives the blow by Levy's resignation,
no one doubts the chance of early elections in Israel has
greatly enhanced. Mark Heller, a political researcher from the
Jaffa Center of Strategic Studies of Tel Aviv University, said
the Netanyahu-led coalition was far more vulnerable than before
due to Levy's resignation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980105.0026 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-04 18:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Levy-Writethru: Levy's Resignation Deals Fatal Blow to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 4 (Xinhua) --
</P>
<P>
Michael Kleiner, a Gesher lawmaker who strongly backed Levy's
action, agreed that the chance for ousting the Netanyahu
government was greater than ever now.
</P>
<P>
Yossi Beilin, lawmaker of the leading opposition Labor Party,
also said that likelihood of early elections is much closer
following Levy's resignation. He appealed to Netanyahu to step down
automatically, citing that he would not last for long since he
would be subjected to more blackmailing by the hardliners within
the government in future.
</P>
<P>
Heller analyzed that it is more likely that 80 lawmakers
will line up to oust Netanyahu to hold new election only for
the prime minister without dissolving the Knesset. Most lawmakers
are more willing to hold early election for only the prime
minister while retaining their Knesset seats. The Israeli law
stipulates that if 80 lawmakers vote against the government,
only new election will be held only for the prime minister
without dissolving the Knesset.
</P>
<P>
So the options for Netanyahu to keep his rule are limited
now: either postponing the budget vote to buy more time to
calm Levy's anger, or surrendering to more pressure of the
hardliners on issues concerning the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Under the Israeli law, Netanyahu can put off the budget
vote until March 31. This will allow him to gain more
maneuvering room to solve the budget crisis by adjusting the
allocation of funds. It will pay off if he could convince
Levy to rescind his resignation.
</P>
<P>
If resorting to the second option, Netanyahu will be again be
cornered soon when the government has to deal with the explosive
issues on the second troops redeployment in the West Bank and the
Israeli-Palestinian final-status talks.
</P>
<P>
The United States is demanding for urgent actions by the
Israeli government to push forward the stalled peace process. If
Netanyahu bows to pressure of the hardliners, other moderates
within the government, such as the popular Defense Minister
Yithzak Mordechai and The Third Way's Public Security Minister
Avigdor Kahalani, will also be forced to quit over further
stagnation in the peace process and bring down the government
consequently. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980105.0027 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-05 </DATE_TIME>
