<HEADLINE> Uzbekistan, Tajikistan Reach Settlement of Debts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, January 4 (Xinhua) -- Uzbekistan and Tajikistan reached
five accords on Sunday, in particular an intergovernmental
agreement on mutual payments for the delivery of goods and gas
supplies in 1998 and Tajikistan's national debt, according to the
Interfax news agency.
</P>
<P>
At the end of a one-day visit by Tajik President Emomali
Rakhmonov to Tashkent Uzbek President Islam Karimov told a press
conference that the Tajik debt reached 180 million U.S. dollars by
January 1, 1997. But now "it is more a matter of mutual payments
than of debt payment," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Tajik debt fell by nearly 30 million U.S. dollar in 1997,
the president said.
</P>
<P>
Karimov said the two sides had an understanding on all issues
such as the internal settlement in Tajikistan, the situation on
the Tajik-Afghan border, the status of Russian troops and regional
security.
</P>
<P>
They also signed a joint communique and agreements on
cooperation in public health, culture, humanitarian aid, science,
technology and information.
</P>
<P>
The Uzbek president meanwhile noted that Tahskent does not want
Tajikistan to become an Islamic state, which would be dangerous
for the people of Uzbekistan.
</P>
<P>
Rakhmonov arrived to Tashkent this morning on a one-day working
visit to Uzbekistan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
