<HEADLINE> Turkey Promised to Combat Illegal Immigration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, January 4 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Foreign Minister Ismail
Cem said here today that Turkey was ready to cooperate with Italy
to combat the illegal immigration.
</P>
<P>
He made the remark in response to his Italian counterpart
Lamberto Dini's letter concerning latest illegal immigration of
Turkish nationals to Italy.
</P>
<P>
Cem said that the current problem is a case of illegal human
smuggling which is an extremely serious form of organized crime.
</P>
<P>
"This criminal activity is based on the exploitation of the
understandable desire to have a better life," Cem said, adding that
Turkey has consistently sought multilateral cooperation against
all forms of organized crime and international terrorism.
</P>
<P>
"We are ready to cooperate with our Italian counterparts on
all possible joint efforts," Cem said.
</P>
<P>
Cem said "We are taking all measures needed to stem illegal
immigration as an organized crime, through or from Turkey."
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Turkey has started to investigate
whether the outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK) is involved in
the illegal traffic of refugees.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has been fighting a separatist war in southeastern
Turkey since August 1984.
</P>
<P>
On December 27 of last year, the Turkish vessel Ararat
with 800 Kurdish refugees on board reached waters near Catanzaro,
Italy.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Interior Minister Murat Baseskioglu said that Turkey
had taken measures on its borders and was negotiating with the
Italian authorities to resolve the problem, adding that Turkey
was ready to welcome back Turkish citizens.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that around 2,000 Kurdish refugees had
arrived in Italy's Adriatic coast since September. 
</P>
