<HEADLINE> Heavy Fighting Erupts in S. Leone's Second City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 4 (Xinhua) -- Heavy fighting broke out this
morning in Sierra Leone's second city Bo in the southeast with
exchanges of artillery fires between forces of the military junta
in power and their Kamajor militia opponents.
</P>
<P>
Casualty figures are yet to be known and there are conflicting
reports from both sides, with each saying they are in control of
the city, according to the British Broadcasting Corporation
monitored here.
</P>
<P>
The Kamajors claimed that several soldiers of the military
government force were killed and fighting was still raging.
</P>
<P>
However, sources closed to the government maintained that the
four-hour fighting had been over before the Kamajors were
repelled. They said the city was now quiet and that there was no
casualty of the government troops.
</P>
<P>
The military government in the capital Freetown also said
reinforcements would be sent to Bo immediately.
</P>
<P>
The Kamajors, a group of traditional hunters fighting for the
restoration of ousted president Ahmed Tejan Kabbah, launched a
new offensive against the junta just before Christmas.
</P>
<P>
The civil defense group, active in areas near the border with
Liberia, also threatened to cut off all the main roads of the
country. 
</P>
