<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-04 19:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Year-ender: Iran Breaks Post-revolution Isolation (by Rong Song) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, January 4 (Xinhua) -- The year 1997 saw an Iran
reaching out to its Arab neighbors and countries in Europe,
scoring marked successes in breaking the isolation it had been
trapped in since its 1979 Islamic revolution.
</P>
<P>
This all started with the change of leadership in the
country. A moderate clergyman, Mohammad Khatami, was elected as
the country's president by a landslide in May. The new president
gave Tehran a face-lift, and, with unprecedented popular support,
held out the olive branch to the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
He did exactly what his predecessors had done before, but this
time his message was duly received and positively responded.
</P>
<P>
First came the Europeans. The European Union (EU) decided in
November to end a half-year-long diplomatic standoff with Iran by
returning their ambassadors to Tehran. The diplomats had been
recalled in April in unison as a sign of protest, after a Berlin
court accused Iranian leaders of involvement in the murder of
Kurdish dissidents in Germany five years ago.
</P>
<P>
Unlike the U.S,, which persisted in isolating and containing
Iran, the European countries preferred an approach of "critical
dialogue" to keep their traditional relationships with the oil-
and gas-rich country they see as a business bonanza.
</P>
<P>
There followed the Arabs as well as Islamic leaders across the
world. The Eighth Summit of the Organization of the Islamic
Conference (OIC) held December in Tehran provided a god-blessed
opportunity for that to happen.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the summit, Khatami sent his foreign minister, Kamal
Kharrazi, on a historic mission to regional states to roadshow
Iran's foreign policy and lobby for their leaders' presence at the
OIC summit.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi went out of his way to convince the Arabs that Iran
poses no threat to them, but rather can be a good neighbor. With
equal, if not more, zeal, he tried to drive a wedge between the
Arabs and the U.S., by citing the tattery Middle East peace
process as a proof of U.S. ulterior motive in the region.
</P>
<P>
This effort paid off. More than 30 presidents, vice presidents,
emirs, crown princes and prime ministers gathered in Tehran on
December 9-11 to discuss the challenges and problems facing the
Muslims, as well as the role of Islamic countries in the future
world.
</P>
<P>
Iran further tapped the summit to its full. Bilateral talks
on improving ties were held with old foes and long-standing
estrangers across the board. Iraq was eager to be one, and Saudi
Arabia and Egypt, the two close allies of the U.S. which oppose
Tehran's export of Islamic revolution, were also on the list.
</P>
<P>
As a result, Tehran lost no time to boast "there is a new
amicable atmosphere in the region for Iran to develop friendly
relations and cooperation with the regional countries."
</P>
<P>
Ironically though, the Americans actually helped in Iran's
drive to break isolation. Failing to exert more pressure on Israel
and push forward the Middle East peace process, the U.S. was blamed
by many Arabs for its biasedness and double-standardness.
</P>
<P>
Its credibility was further hurt by trying, in its revised
d'Amato act, to tighten the extra-territorial screws on foreign
companies that are found to pump more than 20 million dollars into
Iran's oil and gas projects.
</P>
<P>
The arbitrary and high-handed U.S. stance drove an infuriated
Europe rebellious. In September a consortium led by France's oil
giant Total clinched a gas-development accord worth 2 billion
dollars with the National Iranian Oil Company (NIOC). Paris was
quick to the aid of Total by countering the U.S. threat of
punishment.
</P>
<P>
Tehran's global-warming diplomacy is also felt in the ice age
of relations between Iran and the United States. There already
have been advices for U.S. policy changes toward an Iran under a
new and moderate leadership.
</P>
<P>
What becomes obvious is that it is not in the interest of the
U.S. to continue or worsen the present situation of relations
between the U.S. and Iran, now that Washington's isolation and
containment have proved ineffective, observers warned.
</P>
<P>
Rhetorics aside, Washington and Tehran have started sending
signals and taking tentative steps to whittle down hostility. On
November 14, Khatami expressed hope to have a dialogue with the
"great American people," to which U.S. President Bill Clinton
responsed "I would like nothing better than to have a dialogue
with Iran as long as we can have an honest discussion of all the
relevant issues."
</P>
<P>
This past year marked a good beginning of the Khatami
government in Iran, most conspicuously in the field of foreign
relations. But it is without doubt that doubled efforts are
required to keep the current course from roller-coastering.
</P>
</TEXT>
