<HEADLINE> French Minister Backs Early Voting Age at 16 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, January 4 (Xinhua) -- French Minister of National
Education Claude Allegre Sunday expressed his support to early
voting age giving all the youths of France the right to vote at 16
instead of 18.
</P>
<P>
In a statement made at Europe 1 television channel, Allgre said
that the youths of today are different from those of the 1950s, as
they become mature earlier now and have a greater need to be
recognized, to express themselves and to get involved in things.
</P>
<P>
"At 16, we should ask them to choose their nationality. At 16
equally, when they commit offenses, we stress their
responsibility, and we thus treat them as citizens," he said.
</P>
<P>
The French government will start from January 15 an
experimental plan to check violence in schools in several chosen
rough urban areas across the country.
</P>
<P>
"It is to prevent first... and then hold dialogue and make
effort on civic moral education," he said when talking about the
program. "But it is also to remove the troublemakers from the
place where they exercise violence."
</P>
<P>
As for how to deal with the delinquents, Allegre said that it
is "simply to educate them and reinsert them (in society)"
rather than "excluding them and turning them into savage
beasts."
</P>
<P>
In his New Year good wish speech, President Jacques Chirac said
that there is too much violence in schools, streets and public
transport trains and buses in France.
</P>
<P>
Riot by teenagers took place in the eastern city of Strasbourg
on New Year's eve, which greatly shook the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
