<HEADLINE> Playwright Pens Chinese Version of "Schindler's List" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Zhu Shu, a member of the China
Film Association, suggests the production of a Chinese version of
"Schindler's List" to reflect the efforts of foreigners to rescue
local residents during the Nanjing Massacre approximately 60 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
Zhu, also a playwright, has completed a script outlining the
experiences of 20-odd foreigners living in Nanjing in December
1937 when Japanese troops savagely massacred 300,000 Chinese
citizens living in the city.
</P>
<P>
According to Zhu, the foreigners, including John Rabe, the
German social activist who witnessed and recorded the fascist
atrocities in his diary, helped to rescue a greater number of
people than Schindler, a man who helped thousands of Jewish people
escape Nazi concentration camps during the Second World War.
</P>
<P>
Schindler's exploits were adapted into an Oscar-winning movie
in the 1990s, and his name has since been universally
acclaimed. Nonetheless, the deeds of Rabe and a number of other
foreigners in China remain virtually unknown, Zhu said.
</P>
<P>
He acknowledged that the foreigners then living in Nanjing were
real heroes. For example, one American rescued more than 1,000
wounded Chinese soldiers, while another American protected an
untold number of Chinese women from rape and death, and in turn
encouraged them to challenge the bitter hardships.
</P>
<P>
"Efforts to prevent and guide against the revival of militarism
is a very important international subject," according to
Zhu. Critics hold that the subject matter of Zhu's proposed film
bears equal importance with that of "Schindler's List".  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
