<HEADLINE> Jury to Deliberate on Oklahoma Bombing Conspirator's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Jurors in the second trial of
Oklahoma bombing are scheduled to begin considering whether Terry
Nichols should die for conspiring to carry out the Oklahoma City
bombing in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Closing arguments were scheduled today in the penalty phase of
Nichols' trial in Denver, Colorado, to be followed by jury
deliberations, according to media reports.
</P>
<P>
The bombing of the Alfred P. Murrah Federal Building on April
19, 1995, killed 168 people, including 19 children -- the worst
act of terrorism on U.S. soil.
</P>
<P>
Nichols, who was at home with his family in Herington, Kansas,
when the bomb went off, was convicted December 23 of conspiracy
and involuntary manslaughter, but acquitted of first-degree murder
and use of a truck bomb.
</P>
<P>
His army buddy Timothy McVeigh was convicted of all 11 counts,
including conspiracy and first-degree murder. He has appealed both
his conviction and death sentence. 
</P>
