<HEADLINE> Blatter Warns of Exploitation from Commercials </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, January 5 (Xinhua) -- FIFA general secretary Joseph
Sepp Blatter warned of television exploitation on the world most
popular and lucrative sport at the Footbal Expo 98 here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
"We have to portect the game," Blatter said to delegates at the
soccer's first international trade fair. "There is a danger that
our marketing partners are trying to take over the rights of
football associations or clubs."
</P>
<P>
He said the sport has spawned a 200 billion U.S. dollars annual
industry, and directly or indirectly, created 1.2 billion jobs
worldwide.
</P>
<P>
And it may well be that the figures are to be grown with the
advancing of the World Cup which features the most ever 32 tems in
France.
</P>
<P>
But Blatter described the over-involvement of the commercials
and spornsors as "a danger which we have to be careful of" in the
sport, which draw 45 billion viewers every month.
</P>
<P>
Blatter said the ruling on the Jean Marc Bosman's case by the
European Union was "the worst case of political intervention" in
sport.
</P>
<P>
"Football is at risk of losing its local or regional face," he
added when he talked about clubs putting players under a six-year
contracts and selling them after two years.
</P>
<P>
"Please never gamble with our game because it is not just a
game. It is about life," Blatter pleaded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
