<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fossett Lands Round-World Balloon in Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 5 (Xinhua) -- U.S. adventurer Steve Fossett
failed to complete his fourth attempt to pilot a balloon nonstop
around the world as he was forced to land the balloon on the edge
of the Black Sea early today because of low winds and equipment
problems.
</P>
<P>
After flying about a third of the way on his trip, Fossett
decided to end the attempt and land after crossing the Black Sea,
his control team at St. Louis said. He landed at 6:27 a.m. EST
(1127 GMT) about 110 kilometers north of Krasnodar, Russia,
covering about 11,680 kilometers and lasting about four and a half
days.
</P>
<P>
Russian Officials told Fossett's St. Louis control center that
the landing was smooth and Fossett was "OK."
</P>
<P>
"It's just a really, really difficult task to accomplish,"
mission control director Alan Blount said. "We're getting closer."
</P>
<P>
Fossett, a 53-year-old Chicago commodities trader, took off
from St. Louis on Wednesday. He began running into trouble
Saturday when equipment failures caused problems with heat in the
cockpit and directional controls.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, one of the two propane burners that are fired
whenever the hot-air portion of his helium and hot-air craft must
be heated for extra lift was malfunctioning. Fossett was forced
to crawl through the bubble top of his gondola to fire them
manually, allowing more cold air inside.
</P>
<P>
A significant problem was the inability to get the balloon into
the fast-moving subtropical jet stream farther south.
</P>
<P>
Fossett decided to cut short his attempt Sunday evening St.
Louis time, while crossing the Black Sea, Blount said.
</P>
<P>
Fossett still had hoped he might break his own record of
traveling 10,361 miles (about 16,000 kilometers) in a balloon in
six days and two and a half hours. He set the records in January
1997, when he was forced to land in a mustard field in India
because he ran out of fuel.
</P>
<P>
Before 1997, Fossett tried to fly around the world in January
1996, but was forced to land in Canada. In 1995, Fossett had
become the first person to fly solo across the Pacific in a
balloon. Ground control said that he didn't announce it at the
time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980105.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lithuania's Foreign Policy Remains Unchanged: President-Elect </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Lithuania will try, as ever, to
join the European Union, NATO and develop friendly relations with
Russia, President-elect Valdas Adamkus told reporters in Vilnius
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Interfax news agency reported that Adamkus stressed that
"it is very important for us to continue good relations and
cooperation with such a big neighbor as Russia, which is
Lithuania's main economic and trading partner."
</P>
<P>
In response to a question on the status of Russia's Kaliningrad
region, he said: "It makes no sense for Lithuania to raise this
issue," but "if large countries do so, Lithuania will be an active
participant in solving it."
</P>
<P>
Adamkus, 71, won 50.31 percent of votes in the presidential
run-off elections. 
</P>
