<BODY>
<HEADLINE> California to Have Longer School Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, January 4 (Xinhua) -- The school year for public
school students in California, now one of the shortest in the
United States, will be prolonged by eight days starting this year.
</P>
<P>
Under the proposal by Governor Pete Wilson, schools are
required to provide 180 days of instruction, the U.S. national
average, instead of the current 172 days minimum.
</P>
<P>
The proposal was made after polls show education is considered
a top priority for residents in California, where students' scores
have ranked low in recent national exams.
</P>
<P>
Schools are required to offer summer, after-school or weekend
classes for students with below-average reading scores.
</P>
<P>
The 180 days of education, said state officials, is still far
below the averages in Japan and Germany, where students spend more
than 200 days a year in the classrooms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
