<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Over 3,000 S. Korean Busnesses Bankrupt in December </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, January 5 (Xinhua) -- More than 3,000 South Korean
businesses collapsed in December 1997 due to the financial crisis,
the Bank of Korea said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The bank said that 1,226 out of the ill-fated companies were
based in the Seoul area.
</P>
<P>
Stringent monetary policy, high-interest rates and other stiff
terms imposed by the International Monetary Fund (IMF) for its
loans to South Korea were blamed for the record high number of
failed businesses in the month.
</P>
<P>
South Korea has suffered an economic meltdown triggered by the
failure of conglomerates and bad loans of financial institutions
since late 1997, which witnessed the nation's per capita income
drop to 9,400 U.S. dollars from the 10,548 dollars of 1996.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the economic woes would deepen in 1998 as the
nation, under an agreement with the IMF for rescue loans of 57
billion dollars, will have to completely open its financial
market, shut down its ailing commercial and merchant banks and cut
its budget.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the country, with foreign exchange reserve
reportedly standing at 9 billion dollars, has to return 25 billion
dollars in foreign debts before February. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
