<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fossett Landed and Ended His Adventure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, January 5 (Xinhua) -- American Steve Fossett landed
safely in southern Russia and abandoned his third attempt to
become the first man to fly round the world non-stop in a balloon,
an air traffic controller said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The lone 53-year-old adventurer brought down his "Solo Spirit"
balloon some 50 kilometers north of Slavyansk-in-Kuban at 1127
GMT, four days 12 hours and 23 minutes after he launched his craft
from a sports stadium in St. Louis, Missouri.
</P>
<P>
Before the landing, Fossett had spent several hours searching
for a suitable landing site over the Black Sea resort of Anapa.
</P>
<P>
Fossett's spokesman at the Solo Spirit mission control center
in St. Louis could not immediately confirm the landing but Russian
air traffic officials said they had no doubt the balloon had
landed safely in the Krasnodar region.
</P>
<P>
During the day, Fossett's craft had developed a number of
mechanical problems, including a malfunctioning heater inside the
gondola and a broken remote control on one of the gas burners
controlling lift.
</P>
<P>
The malfunction left him freezing and feeling no well and
ensuing consumption problems and unfavourable winds finally led to
his decision to abandon the adventure.
</P>
<P>
Alan Blount, mission control director, told reporters, "The
fact that he hasn't gotten around the world is a disappointment.
But this is a significant achievement. Nobody can diminish that
achievement."
</P>
<P>
Up to now, Fossett has already a record on this trip for the
fastest crossing of the Atlantic by balloon -- 48 hours.
</P>
<P>
Last January, Fossett set a duration and distance record of
more than six days and 16,000 kms when he put down in India.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
