<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Clamp Down on Illegal Capital Flow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 5 (Xinhua) -- China will strive to improve
supervision and control over foreign exchange in 1998, and will
mete out severe punishment for any acts involving the illicit flow
of domestic and international capital.
</P>
<P>
An official from the State Administration for Foreign Exchange
recently told Xinhua that the move is designed to consolidate the
achievements of the nation's financial reform effort and safeguard
the stability of the financial sector.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, China achieved the conditional convertibility of
Chinese currency under current accounts. However, illegal profits
have since been earned from some foreign capital entering the
country.
</P>
<P>
For example, some companies and individuals have evaded the
payment of customs duties or have otherwise smuggled foreign
capital through local foreign trade firms by using fake clearance
documents.
</P>
<P>
In addition, various foreign trade firms have earned
commissions from illegal business transactions.
</P>
<P>
China will work hard to further improve the related laws,
decrees and regulations governing the control of foreign exchange,
so as to help stablize the country's financial order, according to
the official.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
