<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sierra Leonean Troops Clash with Militiamen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Army officers in Sierra Leone
said today that they have killed 25 Kamajors in a "hot pursuit"
battle at Dodo near Kenema in the east of the country.
</P>
<P>
Lieutenant Colonel John Milton, director of defense
information, told Xinhua in a telephone interview that the
Kamajor group was "pursued from Daima in the south to Dodo where
the battle took place."
</P>
<P>
Two government soldiers died in the Daima Songa fight, he
said, adding that the army was able to flush out the Kamajors at
their mini base at Dodo.
</P>
<P>
According to Milton, two attempts to ambush government
soldiers were made at the outskirt of Bo and Giondama between
Saturday and Sunday, both of which were foiled by the military
forces.
</P>
<P>
"The road is no longer closed and commercial vehicles are now
going through," he said.
</P>
<P>
Early today, said Milton, Kamajors attacked government troops
position at Tongo field but were repelled. The army, he said,
captured 15 Kamajor militiamen. There were no losses on the
government side, he added.
</P>
<P>
There are reports of Nigerian troops with the west African
peacekeeping forces known as ECOMOG in neighboring Liberia,
"making their way towards villages on the border with Sierra
Leone" to team up with the Kamajors to launch attacks on Sierra
Leone government soldiers."
</P>
<P>
He said Nigerian troops are also being lifted in large numbers
to Jui, east of the Sierra Leonean capital and the Freetown
International Airport.
</P>
<P>
"These movements are in complete violation of the Conakry
Peace Agreement which outlawed any troop movement or violation of
the ceasefire. They are bent on derailing the ceasefire," Milton
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
