<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Vows to Boost Economy in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 5 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian military government
has geared up for economic development to ensure a smooth
transition to civil rule by October this year.
</P>
<P>
Presenting the 1998 budget Sunday night, Head of State General
Sani Abacha announced that the government has set the growth rate
of gross domestic product at "not less than 5.5 percent" for
1998, the same as last year.
</P>
<P>
Although "the estimated growth of the economy in 1997 was 3.77
percent", lower than the set target, Abacha said "It represented
a marked improvement from the 1.3 percent recorded in 1994; 2.2
percent in 1995 and 3.25 percent in 1996," he added.
</P>
<P>
This year, Abacha said, "the government will therefore adopt
measures to encourage productive activities in various sectors,"
including private enterprises.
</P>
<P>
"Besides, the government will take measures to reflate the
economy in order to raise the purchasing power in the system."
</P>
<P>
The government will try to maintain inflation rate at nine
percent to obtain stability in price and exchange rate in 1998,
while carrying out guided privatization of the existing
state-owned enterprises, economic liberalization and changes in
taxation.
</P>
<P>
The objectives of the budget also include employment creation,
sustained fiscal discipline, appropriate monetary and credit
policy stance, human capital development, improvement of social
and economic infrastructure and sustained transparency,
accountability and comprehensiveness in the conduct of
governance.
</P>
<P>
To meet these goals, Abacha announced an increase in personal
income tax allowances, the abolition of excise duty, continued
incentives for export promotion and civil service reforms, among
other things.
</P>
<P>
All the policies are made apparently by taking recommendations
of the report by the Vision 2010 Committee, which recently
presented the country's first long-term socio-economic
development program toward the year 2010.
</P>
<P>
According to the budget, the country's gross revenue is
estimated at 424 billion Naira (about 5.3 billion U.S. dollars)
and total expenditure at 329 billion Naira (4.11 billion
dollars).
</P>
<P>
That means a budget surplus of 95 billion Naira (about 1.19
billion dollars) for the current fiscal year ending December 31,
1998, which Abacha did not mention in his pre-election speech
read in the country's television and broadcasting network.
</P>
<P>
The head of state, however, admitted that his government
suffered a deficit of five billion Naira (about 62.5 million
dollars) last year.
</P>
<P>
The gross revenue estimated for 1998 include 257 billion Naira
(3.2 billion dollars) from oil sources and 167 billion Naira
(2.09 billion dollars) from non-oil sources.
</P>
<P>
The total expenditure could be broken down as 143 billion
Naira (1.79 billion dollars) for capital expenditure, 117 billion
Naira (1.46 billion dollars) for recurrent expenditure, 44
billion (550 million dollars) reserve for foreign debt, 22
billion Naira (275 million dollars) for domestic debts and three
billion Naira (37.5 million dollars) for local contractors.
</P>
<P>
In its 1997 budget, the Abacha administration projected gross
revenue at 404 billion Naira (5.05 billion dollars) and total
expenditure at 247 billion Naira (3.09 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
As usual, a breakdown of the budget spending is given by the
finance minister several days after the release of the budget.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
