<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Schools Still Closed in Sierra Leonean Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Dozens of primary and
secondary schools in Sierra Leone's capital Freetown remained
closed today despite urgent appeals by the military government to
reopen to start classes.
</P>
<P>
Tuition has been paralysed since the May 25, 1997 coup which
toppled the civilian government of Tejan Kabbah. The Sierra Leone
Teachers Union (SLTU) had ordered all teachers "to stay away from
classes" until democracy is retored in the west African state.
</P>
<P>
"We are utterly shocked over the development as the Department
of Treasury had fully met one of the conditions of the teachers
which is the payment of all delayed salaries. We now owe them
just the salary for December," senior officials from the
Department of Education told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Parents, however, blamed many teachers on "just not turning up
for classes while saying it is the parents who had not sent their
children to schools."
</P>
<P>
Alpha Timbo, secretary of the SLTU, told Xinhua that "problems
still remain which are hampering the commencement of effective
schooling."
</P>
<P>
According to him, the government should pay school and
examination fees for all students who were unbale to sit for
public exams because of the coup.
</P>
<P>
"Many of the students forfeited their cash because they could
not go to the various examination centers due to insecurity at
the time," he said.
</P>
<P>
Timbo said the government must either pay or provide a loan to
the West African Examinations Council (WAEC) to facilitate the
marking of examination papers and payment of invigilators.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, education officials have published the 1998
educational program under which the first term for primary
schools will run for a 14 week period from January 5 to April 8,
second term from April 20 to June 30 with a break between July 1
to 10 and third term from July 13 to September 18.
</P>
<P>
Secondary schools will be in session from January 5 to April 8
with Easter break from April 10 to 14.
</P>
<P>
The second term will be from April 20 to July 30 and third
term from August 4 to September 18. 
</P>
</TEXT>
