<HEADLINE> British Royal Family Focuses on Public Opinion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Queen Elizabeth has called in
market researchers to tell members of the Royal Family what the
public really thinks about them.
</P>
<P>
The Queen's private secretary, Sir Robert Fellowes, has
commissioned the research company, MORI, to undertake an extensive
survey of attitudes toward the monarchy, a Buckingham Palace
spokesman said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The project, which has the full approval of the Queen, was
commissioned about two months ago, shortly after the death of
Princess Diana when the Royal Family was harshly criticized for
appearing unresponsive to the national outpouring of grief.
</P>
<P>
MORI set up what is known as "focus groups" around the country
involving a carefully selected demographic spread.
</P>
<P>
The data has now been completed and MORI's final conclusions
will be presented to Sir Robert shortly. The results, however,
will not be made public.
</P>
<P>
"It is not just a case of another opinion poll. This is
qualitative rather than quantitative research designed to explore
the public's views in a wider context," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The Royal Family was keen to ensure that its work was suited to
the interests and concerns of the British people, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Queen and heir to the throne Prince Charles have made
strenuous efforts to become closer to the people in the past three
months and have been praised by the media for adopting a more
relaxed tone in their public engagements. 
</P>
</TEXT>
