<HEADLINE> Foreign Investment Boosts China's Agricultural Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Increasing agricultural links
China established overseas during 1997 have helped the nation's
agricultural sector maintain the rapid momentum of all-round
sustainable growth, according to the International Business Daily.
</P>
<P>
Gan Zuofu, deputy-director of the International Cooperation
Department under the Ministry of Agriculture, was quoted as saying
that China signed bilateral agreements and memoranda for
agricultural cooperation with more than 20 countries during
1997. China currently conducts agricultural cooperation with more
than a hundred countries.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, China also formed joint committees for agricultural
cooperation with Thailand, Guinea, Egypt, the Netherlands and
Russia, in addition to carrying out scientific and technological
exchanges in the agricultural sector with the World Bank, the
Asian Development Bank, the United Nations Food and Agriculture
Organization (FAO), World Food Program and International Fund for
Agricultural Development.
</P>
<P>
China has imported more than 100,000 varieties of food grain,
cotton, oil crops, fruit, vegetables, herbs, and aquatic, animal
and poultry products, with dozens of said products earning
relevant sectors over one billion yuan (120 million US dollars)
each.
</P>
<P>
China's agricultural sector used foreign funds totalling 5.88
billion yuan from 1991 to the end of 1997, with a large portion of
said funds going for agricultural development in underdeveloped
provinces in northwestern China, including Qinghai and Gansu
provinces.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, China jointly established demonstrations centers with
other countries in 1997 as part of an effort to introduce advanced
techniques, equipment, specie resources and capital.
</P>
<P>
The Netherlands invested five million US dollars in a
demonstration hog breeding center in Beijing, as well as a
gardening center in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
Japan's Mitsubishi Corporation provided three million US
dollars to set up a state-of-the-art gardening center in Beijing
to produced vegetables.
</P>
<P>
Chinese technicians sent to Guinea have also achieved excellent
results in operating a 400 hectare farm. And a program jointly
funded by China and the FAO has helped to improve food production
in Ethiopia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
