<HEADLINE> Moi Sworn in After Winning Multi-Party Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Incumbent Kenyan President
Daniel arap Moi was sworn in today with pledges to curb
corruption and revitalize economy in his fifth and final term
till 2002.
</P>
<P>
Presidents Yoweri Museveni of Uganda and Benjamin Mkapa of
Tanzania attended the inauguration ceremony for the 73-year-old
Kenyan leader along with thousands of cheerful ordinary Kenyans.
</P>
<P>
"Today marks yet another milestone in our political
history...It was a win-win situation for all. KANU (the ruling
party) won, Democracy won, and all Kenyans won," said Moi in his
inauguration speech. He has already been in power for 19 years.
</P>
<P>
The president elect claimed that he would fulfill the pledges
he made in the campaign to improve infrastructure, tackle
poverty, enhance health and education systems, stimulate economic
growth, create more jobs and improve governmental efficiency.
</P>
<P>
"We will be steadfast in our determination to eliminate
corruption," Moi stressed.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, he noted heads of state in eastern Africa "are all
deeply committed to the process of East African Cooperation and
the development of a single market for our three countries."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he ruled out the possibility of forming a
government of national unity as demanded by the opposition, since
his Kenya African National Union (KANU) also won a majority in
the parliamentary elections.
</P>
<P>
He urged the opposition, whose main leaders did not show up at
the ceremony, to accept his victory instead of engaging in
"divisive tribal based politics."
</P>
<P>
Moi asked all his fellow people to try hard to build "a
united, peaceful and prosperous Kenya" under the new government
he is expected to announce soon.
</P>
<P>
In a speech later at the ceremony, the Ugandan president
backed Moi's stance and called on Kenyan opposition parties to
accept the polling results so as not to fuel civil turmoil.
</P>
<P>
"I understand civil strife better than anybody else here. You
start war only if there are no options, but Kenya has options for
changing governments, the option of elections," said Museveni who
took power in 1986 after a five-year guerrilla war.
</P>
<P>
His Ugandan counterpart also echoed the idea, saying that the
Kenyan elections were not rigged and should be accepted.
</P>
<P>
"You (Kenyans) should now move forward and develop your
country," said Mkapa.
</P>
<P>
Moi has garnered at least 2.446 million votes or 40.12 percent
in the country's second multi-party poll held on December 29 and
30. He was followed by Democratic Party Chairman Mwai Kibaki with
1.896 million votes or 31.09 percent.
</P>
<P>
So far there are nine constituencies whose polling results are
yet to come but they "would not make any differences" of the
final outcome, according to Kenyan Electoral Commission Chairman
Samuel Kivuitu.
</P>
<P>
A total of 9,031,141 Kenyans registered for the vote to elect
one president, 210 parliamentary members and 2,955 local
councillors for the next five years starting from 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
