<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Output Value of Pharmaceutical Industry of China Up in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 5 (Xinhua) -- The output value of China's
pharmaceutical industry is estimated at 140 billion yuan
(about 17 billion US dollars) in 1997, up 12.5 percent on the
figure of 1996.
</P>
<P>
"The pharmaceutical industry has begun to develop smoothly,
with the dropping of economic returns slowing down," said Zhang
Wenkang, vice-director of the State Pharmaceutical Administration
of China (SPAC).
</P>
<P>
The added value of the pharmaceutical industry is expected to
reach 38.5 billion yuan (about 4.8 billion US dollars) last year,
up 6.5 percent from the previous year, and its pre-tax profits will
stand at 15.5 billion yuan (about 1.9 billion US dollars), up 17
percent, he said.
</P>
<P>
The sales volume of the pharmaceutical products across the
country in 1997 is estimated at 102 billion yuan (12 billion US
dollars), up 15 percent on 1996.
</P>
<P>
Zhang said the export volume of the pharmaceutical products
will be about 2.1 billion US dollars in 1997, which is almost on a
par with 1996.
</P>
<P>
"The demand of the domestic market had been growing steadily
last year, and the market share of the domestic products,
especially those made by state-run enterprises, had begun to
increase," he added.
</P>
<P>
China has also made progress in drafting and improving the
pharmaceutical legal system, with a series of administrative
regulations concering the management of medicine fairs and
pharmaceutical production issued.
</P>
<P>
"This year, China will focus on accelerating the adjustment of
the pharmaceutical industrial structure, promoting reforms in
the circulation system of the pharmaceutical industry, and
strengthening the administrative inspection," Zhang said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
