<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak Supreme Court to Hear 13th Amendment Case Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's Supreme Court will
on January 12 hear again two petitions challenging the 13th
Amendment to the Constitution which took away the power of the
country's president to dissolve the National Assembly.
</P>
<P>
A five-member bench headed by Chief Justice of the apex court
Ajmal Mian will hear the petitions filed by Naveed Malik and Iqbal
Haider, according to the official Associated Press of Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
The petitions were filed in November 1997 when confrontation
between the government and the judiciary was at its peak.
</P>
<P>
On December 2, 1997, a three-member bench headed by the then
Chief Justice Sajjad Ali Shah heard the petitions and issued an
interim order to suspend the 13th Amendment, re-empowering the
president to dissolve the National Assembly.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, however, a 10-member bench of the Supreme
Court heard petitions against the appointment of Sajjad as chief
justice, declaring that his appointment was improper and his
decisions after November 26, 1997, had no validity and no legal
effect.
</P>
<P>
Only hours after the two benches issued their orders, the then
President Farooq Leghari announced his resignation, thus ending
the four-month-long confrontation between the government and the
judiciary.
</P>
<P>
Sajjad has asked for a two-month leave and he will retire in
February this year.
</P>
<P>
Mian was sworn in as chief justice of Pakistan on December 23,
1997.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980105.0084 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Casualties Reported in North Tibet Snowstorm </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, January 5 (Xinhua) -- No casualties have been reported
in Nagqu Prefecture in the northern part of the Tibet Autonomous
Region, an area hit by heavy snowstorms since last September.
</P>
<P>
Large shipments of relief goods have been sent to the
prefecture in a timely manner over the past few months thanks to
extensive efforts of the central and local governments.
</P>
<P>
Danzin, deputy secretary of the Regional Committee of the
Communist Party of China, said today that relief supplies have
been distributed to victims through various channels.
</P>
<P>
Official figures show that Nagqu has received and distributed
vast quantities of grain and fodder, as well as some 30,000 pieces
of clothing, quilts and other necessities, including fuel.
</P>
<P>
Snowstorms have posed a shortage of both food and fuel and have
created great difficulty to local people, according to local
officials.
</P>
<P>
People throughout the nation have donated to aid the
disaster-stricken area in Tibet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
