<HEADLINE> Alatas: ASEAN Needs "Renewal" to Face Challenges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, January 5 (Xinhua) -- The Association of Southeast
Asian Nations (ASEAN) should make a "renewal" to enable it to cope
with the challenges both inside and outside the region, Indonesian
Foreign Minister Ali Alatas said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
"In a very real sense, what we are witnessing today is a
manifestation of the continuity of the mission of ASEAN as well as
its capacity for renewal," he said at the ceremony marking the
turnover of the post of ASEAN secretary-general from Ajit Singh of
Malaysia to Rodolfo C. Severino of the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Severino, who will serve from 1998 to 2002, officially assumed
office Monday.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN, Alatas said, has been facing a tough time in
expanding its membership, in facing the ASEAN Free Trade Area and
other developments outside the ASEAN.
</P>
<P>
The grouping should thus ensure the continuity of its mission
and at the same time adopt a proactive stance in the face of
profound changes in its political and economic environment.
</P>
<P>
He said the ASEAN has succeeded in bringing political stability
to the region and in stimulating economic cooperation among its
members and dialogue partners.
</P>
<P>
The minister however noted that the recent financial and
monetary crisis has strained the economies of East and Southeast
Asia.
</P>
<P>
"The ASEAN region has taken a severe blow and we must now
summon the faith, the courage and the creativity that attended the
founding and growth of the association to cope with the current
crisis and anticipated challenges and move toward our ultimate
goals," he added. "This means renewal and we are called upon today
to make that renewal."
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN groups Brunei, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia, Myanmar,
the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
