<HEADLINE> TV Documentary to Highlight Life of Zhou Enlai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, January 5 (Xinhua) -- The premiere of a 12-episode
television documentary on the life of late Chinese Premier Zhou
Enlai was held here today as part of ceremonies to mark the 100th
birth anniversary of the great leader on March 5.
</P>
<P>
Provincial and city government officials, as well as Zhou's
relatives, attended the premiere held at Meiyuan Xincun, or New
Plum Villa, Zhou's office when headed the Chinese Communist Party
delegation to peace talks with the Kuomintang from May 1946 to
March 1947.
</P>
<P>
Deng Zaijun, leading producer of the series, said the
documentary includes segments in which 300 well-known figures from
both at home and abroad recount stories of either working with or
meeting Zhou prior to his death in 1976.
</P>
<P>
The documentary also introduces invaluable historical materials
revealed to the public for the first time. Related materials include
the text of a speech Zhou presented to the Military Commission
Conference at the Sixth Congress of the Communist
International in the former Soviet Union in the 1920s, and
notes of his talks with former Soviet leader Stalin.
</P>
<P>
Cambodian King Norodom Sihanouk and former U.S. Secretary of
State Henry Kissinger also revealed some contents of their talks
with Zhou Enlai.
</P>
<P>
The epic documentary, which was inspired by Zhou's relatives
and former staffers, was jointly produced by Beijing Television
Station and the China International Cultural Exchange Center.
</P>
<P>
Nanjing Television Stations will begin airing the series this
evening.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
