<HEADLINE> Suifenhe Becomes Favorite Trade Channel to Northeast Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Suifenhe, a border city in
northeast China's Heilongjiang Province neighboring on Russia, has
emerged as a favorite trade channel linking China, Russia, Japan
and the Republic of Korea.
</P>
<P>
According to a report in today's International Business Daily,
Suifenhe witnessed a record trade volume of 1.3 million tons of
commodities valued at 478.69 million US dollars for the first 11
months of 1997.
</P>
<P>
The border city's total trade volume in whole the year is
expected to reach 1.4 million tons.
</P>
<P>
The increase in cross-border trade has been attributed, at
least in part, to a 1996 agreement the city government signed with
Russia, the Republic of Korea (ROK), Japan and the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region (HKSAR). The agreement call for
northeast China to transport goods directly to Japan, the ROK, the
HKSAR and Russia via Suifenhe and Nahodka, a major Russian port. A
number of domestic and international traders have shifted the
focus of their business operations to Suifenhe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
