<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-05 13:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Discussed Current Political Crisis With </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu held consultations Monday morning with Knesset
(parliament) members of Likud and coalition parties on the current
political crisis erupted following the resignation of the Foreign
Minister David Levy.
</P>
<P>
During the consultations, Likud Knesset member Gideon Ezra
proposed to Netanyahu that he should appoint National
Infrastructure Minister Ariel Sharon as acting Deputy Prime
Minister and Foreign Minister and Dan Meridor, another Likud
Knesset member, to take the post as National Infrastructure
Minister.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu did not make his final decision on such issues, but
did ask all coalition Knesset members to vote for the 1998 state
budget later this afternoon in the Knesset, government sources
said.
</P>
<P>
The Knesset is scheduled to start another round of debate on
the arrangement bill of the state new budget at 2:00 PM (local
time) today before its second and third readings.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the High Court of Justice declared Monday invalid
the agreement reached between the Finance Ministry and the
religious parties of the coalition concerning the allocation of
funds for Yeshiva students in the 1998 budget as petitioned by
the Labor Party.
</P>
<P>
The Court ordered the Finance Ministry to tell the Knesset
the Court's decision and cut the allocations in the new state
budget, saying such agreement could only cause more conflicts
between vast majority ordinary and Yeshiva students.
</P>
<P>
David Levy announced his resignation on Sunday, accusing the
government of not keeping its promises made last summer on
budget allocations to his party and the new state budget did
not address the problems of the poor.
</P>
<P>
Four hours after Levy's resignation announcement, Netanyahu
also addressed the whole nation through TV that he hopes David
Levy will retract his resignation.
</P>
<P>
But between the lines, it has been clear that Netanyahu did
not really want Levy to return to the government.
</P>
<P>
He said he would hold onto the Foreign Affairs portfolio for
the time being, and would continue the talks on redeployment once
the budget is passed in the Knesset.
</P>
<P>
President Ezer Weizman on Sunday night called Levy to come
back for the sake of the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai also said last night that
Levy is important and essential in the government to further the
peace process, establish security and deal with the socio-economic
issues.
</P>
<P>
Other cabinet ministers including the Science Minister Michael
Eitan, Health Minister Yehoshua Matza, Interior Minister Eli
Suissa, also asked Levy to stay in the coalition.
</P>
<P>
But till now, there is no sign of levy's return.
</P>
<P>
The surprise resignation of levy left the government standing
weakly on its feet. His departure is politically devastating not
just because the Gesher (Levy's Bridge Party) faction represents
five Knesset seats, bringing the coalition a razor-thin majority
of 61 seats only in the 120-member Knesset, but also a huge
political damage to the coalition headed by Netanyahu. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
