<BODY>
<HEADLINE>   Greece Introduces Alternative Conscription for Objectors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Greece has introduced an
alternative and unarmed conscription for conscientious objectors
since the beginning of this year.
</P>
<P>
A law passed in last June provides for conscientious objectors
to serve 30 months in the army, or 32 months in the air force or
33 months in the navy.
</P>
<P>
But under the unarmed military service system, conscientious
objectors will serve an additional 12 months to the regular
conscription in the three arms, the semi-official Athens News
Agency (ANA) reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The alternative conscription system stipulates that
conscientious objectors will have to serve an additional 18 months
to the regular conscription.
</P>
<P>
Conscientious objectors opting for public service will serve 36
months, 38 months and 39 months in lieu of the army, the air force
and the navy respectively.
</P>
<P>
Conscientious objectors choosing either unarmed military
service or alternative conscription will not have chance to serve
in military units or public service in the cities such as Athens,
Thessaloniki, Patras and Larissa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980105.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southeast Asia Crisis Harms Bangladesh Labor Export </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, January 5 (Xinhua) -- The serious economic crisis in the
Southeast Asian region appears to be a setback for Bangladesh's
labor export, a local newspaper reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
About 250,000 Bangladeshis are now working legally in Malaysia,
where thousands of others are also staying illegally, The Daily
Star said.
</P>
<P>
About 1 million migrant laborers, mostly from Indonesia, would
lose their jobs in Malaysia due to the economic crisis that
gripped the entire Southeast Asian region, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Many of Bangladeshis now working in Malaysia will lose their
jobs because of the suspension of many development projects as a
result of the recession.
</P>
<P>
About 4,000 Bangladeshis, who are already over-staying in South
Korea, would have to be repatriated as the country would no longer
allow them to work there.
</P>
<P>
Labor export is a major foreign exchange earner for this South
Asian country, which exports more than 1 million workers every
year.
</P>
<P>
The country, which exports labor mainly to Malaysia, Saudi
Arabia and South Korea, earned 1.34 billion U.S. dollars in
foreign exchange in the 1995-96 fiscal year. Expatriate
Bangladeshi workers remitted about 1.4 billion dollars from
January to November last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
