<HEADLINE> Cholera Kills 40 Ugandans Since Christmas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Cholera has killed at least 40
Ugandans since Christmas, local media reported today.
</P>
<P>
A new outbreak of the pandemic has claimed 36 in eastern Mbale
district alone, The New Vision said in its report, adding the
disease has also killed three in Luzira Prison which houses 1,900
prisoners here in the capital.
</P>
<P>
The first outbreak of the disease in Mbale occurred three
weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
Richard Othieno, the district health officer of Mbale,
attributed the new wave of the disease to a delay in burying the
deceased so that all relatives would be present at the burial as
required by the African tradition.
</P>
<P>
On Sese islands in Lake Victoria, local authorities have
registered 15 deaths so far. A local reporter saw a child
drinking water directly from the lake. He also cited the lack of
toilets as a cause for the spread of the epidemic.
</P>
<P>
Peace Onzia, an official in Mbale, said only 30 percent of
homesteads in the district have latrines.
</P>
<P>
In Kampala, the capital, the conditions are improving. But
1,000 cholera cases had been reported since Christmas, the
newspaper quoted experts as saying.
</P>
<P>
Tom Koene, the country's representative to Medicines San
Frontiers (MSF:doctors without borders), said the average daily
record of cholera cases dropped from 250 to 150 in Mulago
Hospital, the most up-to-date one in the country.
</P>
<P>
But Marie Skiinnider, coordinator of the MSF, said some people
are misusing antibiotics in fighting against the epidemic and
warned of the danger of forming a resistant strain of the germ.
</P>
<P>
Sam Okware, head of the anti-cholera task force, had appealed
to the local people to send patients to treatment centers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980105.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Speeds up Nuclear Power Plant Construction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 5 (Xinhua) -- China will speed up construction
of four cross-century nuclear power plants with installed
generating capacity totaling 6.6 million kw, in a bid to boost the
country's nuclear power development.
</P>
<P>
This was learned from a work conference of the China National
Nuclear Corporation (CNNC) held here today.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the second-phase project of the Qinshan Nuclear
Plant in east China's Zhejiang province and the Ling'ao Nuclear
Power Plant in south China's Guangdong province which were
launched in May and June of 1997, the country will start to build
the third-phase project of the Qinshan Nuclear Power Plant at the
end of this year, building two generating sets each with installed
capacity of 700,000 kw, and the Lianyungang Nuclear Plower Plant
in east China's Jiangsu province in 1999, building two generating
sets each with installed capacity of one million kw.
</P>
<P>
Chinese premier Li Peng has written a letter to the conference,
speaking highly of the country's nuclear power development.
</P>
<P>
He said that a new-type nuclear scientific-industrial system
embracing defense industry and non-military enterprises has
basically taken shape in the country.
</P>
<P>
"The coming three years is crucial for the country's nuclear
power development, " said vice-president Zhuang Huazhu of CNNC,
adding that installation and trial operation of the four large
nuclear power plants will be conducted during the period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
