<DOCNO> XIE19980105.0106 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Economy to Face Big Challenges: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 5 (Xinhua) -- South African Finance
Minister Trevor Manuel has warned that the country's economy is
facing immense challenges this year as foreign investors are
expecting high from it, the Business Day newspaper reported
today.
</P>
<P>
"We are taking everyone into our confidence about the
immensity of the challenge. So many of the indicators are moving
in the right direction and South Africa remains an exceedingly
important investment destination," he said in an interview last
week.
</P>
<P>
But he said the country's overall economic conditions are
improving despite instability on global markets, a sharp fall in
the gold price and poor fiscal controls by provincial
governments.
</P>
<P>
Manuel indicated that investors should not judge the country's
economic health only by watching how closely the government's
economic projections are reflected. They should "look at the
overall performance" and take into account "factors over which
one has little or no control".
</P>
<P>
The government's medium-term budget expected the economy to
grow about 3 percent this year, and 4 percent and 5 percent in
subsequent years. This falls short of the 3.8 percent, 4.9
percent and 6.1 percent growth targets set for 1998-2000 by the
Growth, Employment and Redistribution (GEAR) macro-economic
strategy.
</P>
<P>
GEAR, adopted in 1996 by the government, highlights a
competitive fast-growing economy based on export improvement so
as to create sufficient jobs, and a redistribution of income and
opportunity in favor of the poor.
</P>
<P>
Manuel attributed the failure in meeting the target to
uncontrollable elements, such as global market instability and
poor gold prices.
</P>
<P>
"The balance of payments constraint is still there, and the
impact of the low gold price on jobs could be formidable. That is
why GEAR targets growth in non-gold exports. There has been some
success in stimulating manufactured exports," he said.
</P>
<P>
The fundamentals would continue to improve as the government
sticks to GEAR strategy, the medium-term expenditure framework
and the Reconstruction and Development Program (RDP), Manuel
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
