<HEADLINE> S. Africa' SOS Phones Vandalized on Major </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 5 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's Transport
Department is losing one million Rand (210,000 U.S. dollars) a
year on its SOS telephones set up along the major highways due to
vandalism, local daily Business Day reported today.
</P>
<P>
Transport ministry spokesman Didi Moyle was quoted as saying
that the department was "fighting a losing battle because as fast
as the phones are being repaired, they are being vandalized."
</P>
<P>
Moyle said she could not say how many of the telephones had
been operational during the festive season because they were
continuously vandalized and the batteries and solar panels were
often stolen.
</P>
<P>
"We can't understand why these phones are being vandalized
because there is nothing of value on them," she said.
</P>
<P>
The department had introduced an incident management system
where motorists could dial 112 on a cellular phone, if they had
one, or 10177 on the SOS telephones if they could find one that
was working.
</P>
<P>
The department was reportedly negotiating a deal with one of
the cellular network companies in an attempt to convert the SOS
telephones into a system that could be used more effectively.
</P>
</TEXT>
