<HEADLINE> S. African Former President Blasts Truth Body </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 5 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's former
state president P W Botha blasted the Truth and Reconciliation
Commission (TRC) again on Sunday, saying that he was still not
prepared to appear before it.
</P>
<P>
"I have done nothing to them but they have started prosecuting
me," Botha was quoted as saying in an interview with an Afrikaans
Sunday newspaper, Rapport.
</P>
<P>
He said he had done nothing wrong and that he went to great
lengths in giving a written reply to all questions put to him by
the TRC concerning the former State Security Council in an
1,800-page document.
</P>
<P>
TRC laid criminal charges against Botha after he failed to
appear before the TRC for a third time last month.
</P>
<P>
Western Cape Attorney-General Frank Kahn said he would decide
on the matter this week.
</P>
<P>
Tension between Botha and the TRC flared up when Botha told
Rapport in mid-November that he would rather be prosecuted than
appear before the TRC.
</P>
<P>
TRC Chairman Desmond Tutu, who was angry with Botha's attitude
toward his commission, failed to lay charges against him on
December 5 only as a result of a defection of the subpoena.
</P>
<P>
A third subpoena was served on the same day, ordering Botha to
appear on December 19 but Botha failed again to turn up.
</P>
<P>
Botha, who was president between 1984 and 1989, had refused to
apologize for the activities of his government, which vehemently
implemented apartheid policies.
</P>
<P>
He accused the TRC of being a revenge camp against the
Afrikaner and called it a "circus."
</P>
<P>
The TRC was installed after the first all-race general
election in 1994 to investigate human rights violations in the
apartheid era. 
</P>
</TEXT>
