<HEADLINE> At Least 11 Massacred on Lesotho-S. African </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 5 (Xinhua) -- At least 11 people were
shot and hacked to death near the border between South Africa and
Lesotho on New Year's Day, South African Press Association quoted
police as saying today.
</P>
<P>
Police officer Fanie Lategan who attended the scene said the
bodies were found scattered near the Bellevue patrol post on
Friday after police were alerted about the massacre.
</P>
<P>
Lategan said an AK-47 assault rifle was found in the
possession of one of the victims.
</P>
<P>
He said the victims were apparently from the Nzongwane area in
the Eastern Cape Province.
</P>
<P>
They had apparently crossed into Lesotho via Kwazulu-Natal and
allegedly stole cattle from Lesotho residents.
</P>
<P>
Another police officer, Fanie de Lange, said the attack
appeared to be related to the ongoing conflict between Nzongwane
residents and those of Lesotho.
</P>
<P>
Investigations were hampered by poor visibility and difficult
terrain, de Lange said.
</P>
<P>
Lategan said it took police almost a whole day to locate one
of the bodies.
</P>
<P>
According to De Lange, it was possible that more people were
killed in the attack.
</P>
<P>
Several incidents of cattle rustling were reported on the
border area in recent days. 
</P>
