<HEADLINE> Communications Contracts Signed For Australian Armed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Australia's communication and
electronics industry received a boost Monday, winning contracts
with the Australian Defense Force (ADF) to develop a high
frequency radio communications system for the armed forces.
</P>
<P>
Australian Defense Minister Ian McLachlan Monday announced the
signing of the contracts worth more than 380 million Australian
dollars (247 million U.S. dollars) between the ADF and Boeing
Australia Limited to operate a modern communications system well
into the next century.
</P>
<P>
McLachlan said the contracts were the largest awarded for a
communications project in as many years and would provide a
substantial boost for the country's communication and electronics
industries.
</P>
<P>
"About 75 percent of the contract to develop and construct the
network and more than 90 percent of the operation and support
contract will be provided locally," he said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
McLachlan said the system would use modern technology to
provide a long-range communications system for use within
Australia and with ships and aircraft operating in the region.
</P>
<P>
It will comprise four ground communications stations located in
the New South Wales state's Riverina region, Townsville in
northern Queensland state, Darwin, a port city in northern
Australia and at the North West Cape in Western Australia state.
</P>
<P>
Each station would have a transmitter and receiver site
remotely controlled by a network facility in Canberra, capital of
Australia.
</P>
<P>
McLachlan said the network was scheduled to commence initial
operations in 2002 and would be fully operational by late 2004.
</P>
</TEXT>
