<DOCNO> XIE19980105.0118 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Weaker, Dragged Down by Asian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 5 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar shrugged
off strong international trade figures Monday and was dragged down
below 65.00 US cents by struggling Asian currencies to close at
its lows for the session.
</P>
<P>
On its first day of full strength trading since the Christmas
and New Year breaks, the local currency finished at 64.82 US
cents, down from 65.05 locally late on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The 497 million Australian dollars (323 million US dollars)
balance on goods and services surplus for November announced by
the Australian Bureau of Statistics Monday was not enough to lift
the local currency from its doldrums.
</P>
<P>
Stavros Nitis, foreign exchange senior dealer of Commonwealth
Bank of Australia, said the market briefly rallied to 65.15 US
cents following the release of the data, but then fell back to
previous levels around 65.05.
</P>
<P>
"I think the market has just shrugged those numbers off as
historical data and of not too much significance," Nitis said.
</P>
<P>
Colonial State Bank economist Craig James said today's figures
were subject to volatility and export growth would slow in 1998 as
demand from Asia was falling.
</P>
<P>
"It is probably a case of the calm before the storm," he said.
</P>
<P>
Of greater concern than the local data Monday was plunging
Southeast Asian currencies.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian rupiah, the Malaysian ringgit, the Philippine
peso and the Thai baht all recorded new lows.
</P>
<P>
Traders said Asian currencies were being sold down on domestic
concerns coupled with lingering fears that more turbulence lies
ahead for Asia before recovery sets in from the regional financial
turmoil raging since July.
</P>
<P>
Nitis said the Australian dollar would see a gradual decline on
the back of deterioration in Asia, and lower commodity prices.
</P>
<P>
"I think over the next week or two we are going to revisit the
previous lows, which are around 64.20/30," he said.
</P>
<P>
The currency has not been at these levels since September 1993.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar ended Monday at 85.73 yen, from 85.19 on
Friday and at 1.1673 marks, from 1.1720.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
