<HEADLINE> Australian Shares Jump As Banks Rise on Bonds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 5 (Xinhua) -- The Australian share market
moved strongly higher Monday as a buoyant bond market pushed
banking stocks up with sellers still largely absent from trading.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index rose 35.2 points to 2,644.3, following
the rise on Wall Street on Friday and ignoring further falls on
key Asian equity markets.
</P>
<P>
"Banks are strong with quality earnings in a low inflation
environment, coupled with the fact (US Federal Reserve chairman)
Greenspan is talking deflation, disinflation and the diminishing
of asset values," said Stuart Smith from Henderson Charlton Jones.
</P>
<P>
Smith said buyers were looking to invest in blue chip stocks
with assured earnings, including banks and high yielding property
trusts, as a buffer against the predicted deflationary
environment.
</P>
<P>
Volume was still below average in a continuation of the holiday
environment, which caused a possible exaggeration of gains in the
market, he said.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 235.5 million shares at a value of 763
million Australian dollars (496 million US dollars), with rises
outnumbering falls 577 to 414.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index rose 63.5 points to 4,523.9.
</P>
<P>
Westpac and Commonwealth Bank shares benefited the most in the
bank buy-up, increasing 23 cents and 40.6 cents respectively.
Meanwhile, ANZ Bank improved 13 cents and National Australia Bank
lifted 31.1 cents.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index was 12 points higher at 1,146.1, with
mining stocks strong.
</P>
<P>
BHP shares improved 12 cents and Rio Tinto and WMC were both
six cents better than last session.
</P>
<P>
Gold stocks generally improved as the bullion price rose by
0.20 US dollar per ounce to 287.85.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
