<DOCNO> XIE19980105.0122 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Attention Called to Enterprise Groups in China (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Researchers at the
Macro-economics Institute of China's State Planning Commission
warn that more attention should be paid to six aspects of large
enterprise groups because their problems will directly affect
their development.
</P>
<P>
A strategy of making conglomerates and enterprises groups out
of state-owned enterprises as a reform measure is natural they say.
</P>
<P>
General Secretary Jiang Zemin, in his report to the 15th
National Party Congress, said an effort should be made to set up
more multinational conglomerates with mixed ownership to increase
large enterprise reforms and expansion.
</P>
<P>
So, conglomerates and enterprise groups have been growing in
China but, in the wake of this quick expansion, a range of
problems have emerged and greater attention should be paid to them.
</P>
<P>
Some enterprise groups and government departments are paying
too much attention to size and want to grow overnight. Some have
expressed a clear desire to become one of the world's top 500
conglomerates by early next century, but the feasibility of this
is quite doubtful.
</P>
<P>
Enterprises can be developed by internal or external
expansion. Internal comes about through capital accumulation, and
expanding into related products or industries by using
technological, financial, and management advantages. External
comes about through mergers and reorganization of assets.
</P>
<P>
Quite a number of enterprise groups and government departments,
deeming that joining the world's top 500 by internal expansion
will just take too long, turn to external expansion. But that is
not as good as improving scientific research and development or
management and will only lead to failure. The enterprise groups of
the Republic of Korea (ROK) are a good example of this.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980105.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Attention Called to Enterprise Groups (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A second problem is that some conglomerate executives and a
number of government authorities confuse economies of scale with
economic scale.
</P>
<P>
In terms of assets and sales, most Chinese enterprises are
small in scale and are not very efficient, and they believe that
one way to develop economies of scale is to put all related
business in one enterprise group, but this larger scale is not
necessarily economies of scale.
</P>
<P>
China established a number of large enterprises or enterprise
groups, thinking of economies of scale or separate areas of
specialization, but few of these were successful.
</P>
<P>
What is needed is to look at strong points or return on
production in establishing enterprise groups. In setting them up,
acquisitions and takeovers, two popular practices in a market
economy, should be considered fundamental, and not administrative
orders. Otherwise, some enterprises with good performance records
will eventually be landed in a difficult situation by money-losing
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
A third problem is that some enterprises groups are paying too
much attention to diversifying economic operations, with the idea
of spreading the risks. But, even though a strategy of diverse
operations can be an important choice for large enterprise groups
in expanding their business, diversity does not always lead to a
decrease in risks, and diversification can sometimes only further
increase risks.
</P>
<P>
It is more efficient for enterprises to concentrate on limited
expansion, as in the case of the Seg Group of Shenzhen City, in
south China's Guangdong Province.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980105.0124 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FINA Restricts Submarine Butterfly Starts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 5 (Xinhua) -- The International Amateur
Swimming Federation (FINA) announced in Perth on Monday that they
will restrict the distance of submarine technique in butterfly,
which has contributed to a few world records in recent years.
</P>
<P>
FINA voted to define a rule which already uses in breaststroke
and backstroke and limit the distance allowed to be swum under
water to 15 meters.
</P>
<P>
A FINA technical congress said the above and other new rules
would come into effect on March 6.
</P>
<P>
The butterfly world record holders, such as Russian reigning
Olympic champion Denis Pankratov and American Misty Hyman were
greatly benefited from the prolonged submarine techniques, even
more than half the first length of the 50-meter pool uner water.
</P>
<P>
The congress not only agreed in principle to introduce
semifinals in swimming, but also decided to recognise world
records for all other three 50 meters strokes, like butterfly,
breaststroke and backstroke in the long-course pool besides
freestyle, the same as its treatment of short-course records.
</P>
<P>
Competition organisers may consider whether to use the
two-start rule which allows for one false start at current major
championships, or the one-start rule with no false starts
allowed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980105.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Attention Called to Enterprises Groups (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A fourth problem is over-emphasis of low-cost expansion. A
vital reform measure of state-owned enterprises is to enliven the
state-owned economy. Many enterprise groups have expanded quickly
through acquisitions, mergers, and reorganization of assets and
have developed medium-sized and small enterprises.
</P>
<P>
However, some enterprises groups emphasize low-cost expansion
and open new factories or purchase many small enterprises,
resulting in rapid expansion, rapid rise of management costs, and
a drop in efficiency.
</P>
<P>
In strategies and policies that affect long-term development,
higher cost may bring more benefits and be considered low in the
long term. But, if good strategies and plans are not implemented,
or if wrong strategies are carried out, the low-cost expansion may
ultimately carry a heavy price, as in the case of Japan's Sony in
the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
A fifth problem is that it is wrong to think of assets as being
more important than productive operation. Quite a number of people
believe that assets are a kind of higher form and that enterprises
should shift from production to assets.
</P>
<P>
Many executives think of assets as an independent business and
blindly lead their company into the financial sector, showing keen
zeal for shares and futures to the neglection of their main
business and production.
</P>
<P>
In fact, assets are the business of financial organizations
like investment banks and foundations, but for non-financial
enterprises, especially manufacturers, assets are only a part of
their overall work, and are not at all a higher operation or the
purpose of a company.
</P>
<P>
A sixth and final problem is that some enterprise groups set up
in the past have expanded too fast, and a number of them, which
are bound together through administrative order, do not have very
advanced relations between the general office and the subsidiaries
and lack strong cohesiveness because of imperfect management, and
can not develop economies of scale.
</P>
<P>
Large enterprise groups should intensify construction and
offices should form a complete system of production, marketing,
technological growth, financial control, and assets operations.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980105.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-05 </DATE_TIME>
