<HEADLINE> Malaysia's State Bank Allowed to Intervene in Forex: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Deputy Prime
Minister Anwar Ibrahim announced Monday that the country's Central
Bank is allowed to intervene in the foreign exchange to ensure the
stability of the local currency ringgit, provided that it is
"deemed absolutely necessary".
</P>
<P>
The ringgit went passed the level of four ringgit to the U.S.
dollar Monday, a new historical low. At the day's close, the local
currency stood at 4.0550/50 against the greenback.
</P>
<P>
The fall in ringgit was attributed mainly to regional factors.
</P>
<P>
"As a policy, the State Bank has to ensure that there is
stability of the ringgit," Anwar, who is also finance minister,
told reporters after a function here.
</P>
<P>
"I don't think they should preclude the option to intervene
where deemed absolutely necessary," he said. "As a practise, State
Bank has not intervened too aggressively to defend the ringgit,
but it should keep the option (of intervening)."
</P>
<P>
He said the central bank must have the credibility and power to
safeguard and defend the country's financial system, including the
stability of the ringgit, when it thinks that is necessary.
</P>
<P>
"The performance of the general development in the region is a
concern to us," Anwar said. "We will continue to monitor the
situation. I believe we can overcome this."  
</P>
</TEXT>
