<HEADLINE> Computers to Have Human Brain Power: Expert </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Rapid growth of information
technology will usher in "terra computers" by 2010 which can
process 1 trillion instructions per second, an expert said Monday
at the 85th Indian Science Congress being held in the southern
city of Hyderabad.
</P>
<P>
The 85th Indian Science Congress, which opened last Saturday,
is attended by 5,000 delegates from both home and abroad.
</P>
<P>
"Computers are fast catching up with the human brain and the
day is not far away when micro-chips would process 1 trillion
operations per second, which is close to human brain power,"
Professor Raj Reddy of the Carnegie Mellon University of the
United States said.
</P>
<P>
On future trends and applications of information technology, he
said, "intuitive interface" computers would soon replace the
mouse-driven operations with visual and speech-recognition
systems.
</P>
<P>
By 2020, 100 billion transistors could be accommodated on a
single chip, he said.
</P>
<P>
The rapid growth in information technology is leading to a
paradigm shift in all intellectual endeavors with an
all-encompassing impact. "Unless pro-active steps are taken, the
emerging technological growth will lead to a widening gap between
the haves and have-nots," he warned.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
