<HEADLINE> Share Prices Continue to Fall on Singapore Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Share prices continued to
decline in thin trading on the Singapore market as the benchmark
Straits Times Industrials Index (STII) lost another 22.25 points
to close at 1,495.95 points on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that stocks went lower as the market was burdened
by the seemingly unceasing weakness in regional currencies and the
increasing desire among investors to hold cash.
</P>
<P>
They noted that most Asian currencies were generally softer,
with the Indonesian rupiah, the Thai baht and the Malaysian
ringgit all plunging to all-time lows earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
The total market volume was low at 64.45 million units, valued
at 133.96 million Singapore dollars (about 78.34 million U.S.
dollars). Declines overwhelmed advances by 278 to 41, while 292
other counters remained unchanged.
</P>
<P>
Summit was the most actively traded stock as it registered a
turnover of 3.23 million units. It was followed by IPC Corporation
which had 2.38 million shares traded. Singapore Telecom was next
with 2.26 million shares changed hands.
</P>
<P>
Jardine Matheson Holdings (JMH) led the gainers of the day as
it rose by 25 cents to finish at 5.3 U.S. dollars. GP Bat
increased by 16 cents to end at 4.56 Singapore dollars, while
Clipsal picked up by 15 cents to close at 1.55 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, J Cement and Uniphoenix shared the top spot on
the gainers' list as each of them declined by 40 cents to end at
five and 2.5 Singapore dollars respectively. Malaya Banking fell
by 34 cents to close at 4.18 Singapore dollars. Asia Pacific and
the Singapore Press Holdings (SPH) Foreign were 30 cents lower at
four Singapore dollars and 20.8 Singapore dollars respectively.
</P>
