<DOCNO> XIE19980105.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila to Keep Inflation Rate at Single-Digit Level </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 5 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government is
determined to keep the inflation rate within single digit for the
year 1998 despite the continuing assault on Asian currencies,
Socioeconomic Planning Secretary Cielito Habito said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Habito's statement followed the release of the December
inflation figure of 6.1 percent compared to November's 6.5
percent.
</P>
<P>
The December figure brought the 1997 full-year average
inflation rate to 5.1 percent, compared to the 1996 rate of 8.4
percent and below the government's 6- to 6.5-percent target for
the year.
</P>
<P>
The lower-than-expected inflation rate could be attributed to
low prices of most commodities in December, especially of food,
beverages and tobacco, data released by the National Statistics
Office showed on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Habito, who is also director-general of the National Economic
and Development Authority (NEDA), cited "a policy environment that
fosters greater competition in the economy" as one of the reasons
for the lower inflation figures.
</P>
<P>
Habito said manufacturing firms have been reluctant in
adjusting their prices due to intense competition in the economy.
</P>
<P>
Stable prices were also made possible through early rice
importation, active price monitoring and avoiding of a wage-price
spiral, he added.
</P>
<P>
The ample supply of fruit and vegetables during the holiday
season, he said, also contributed to the low inflation rate.
</P>
<P>
Habito, however, maintained that the government is "watchful"
of the danger signs, particularly the current currency crisis, the
El Nino phenomenon which would cause food prices to rise and
higher election spending.
</P>
<P>
He called for the adoption of economic measures, particularly
prudent monetary and fiscal management and a six-point agenda to
address the currency situation and keep inflation under control.
</P>
<P>
Habito noted that the Central Bank, in particular, intends to
pursue prudent monetary management to address the expected surge
of prices.
</P>
<P>
He said the NEDA projected the full-year inflation rate at 6.5
to 7.5 percent for 1998, taking into account likely wage and oil
price adjustments due to the continued fall of the peso.  
</P>
</TEXT>
