<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Adamkus Wins Lithuanian Election With Slim Majority </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Valdas Adamkus, a U.S.
ecologist of Lithuanian descent, has won the Lithuania's
presidential election runoff with a slim majority, the
Interfax news agency reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Adamkus, a 71-year-old right-centrist, got 50.48 percent votes
while his rival -- left centrist lawyer Arturas Paulauskas, 44,
had 49.26 percent of the votes.
</P>
<P>
Adamkus was born in Kaunas, Lithuania, in 1926. His family
emigrated to Germany in 1944. He lived in the United States from
1949 until June 1997. Holding dual citizenship of Lithuania and
the United States, he has been a regional administrator at the
U.S. environmental Protection Agency for 16 year.
</P>
<P>
The official results will be announced by January 9. The new
president will take oath and start this term February 25. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
