<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ADB Urges Vietnam to Speed Up Economic Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 5 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank (ADB)
Monday urged Vietnam to accelerate its current economic reform
process to avoid a currency crisis.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam can minimize the impact of the Asian currency crisis on
its economy through good macroeconomic management and by speeding
up its economic reform, including deregulation and liberalization,
the Manila-based bank said in a news release.
</P>
<P>
The ADB said this is the consensus reached by economic experts
at the High Level Policy Seminar on the Financial Developments in
Asia and Vietnam's Economy recently held in Hanoi.
</P>
<P>
The seminar, organized by the ADB, the State Bank of Vietnam
and the Central Institute for Economic Management, was attended by
senior government officials and representatives from the
International Monetary Fund, the World Bank and the U.N.
Development Program.
</P>
<P>
The experts agreed that Vietnam's exchange rate policy needs to
be flexible to avoid a significant appreciation of the currency in
real terms, the ADB said.
</P>
<P>
The liberalization of the production sector, the financial
sector and the external capital account need to be carefully
sequenced and not prematurely implemented and it should be
accompanied by a solid legal and accounting system and good
prudential oversight of the financial system, the experts said.
</P>
<P>
The reform of state-owned enterprises, which still play a
dominant role in the economy, remains critical and should be
encouraged so as not to restrict the needed reforms in the
financial sector, the experts noted.
</P>
<P>
External resource flows must be encouraged in view of low
domestic savings and should be efficiently allocated to the
productive sectors, based on Vietnam's comparative advantage.
</P>
<P>
As competition for foreign direct investments increases
substantially, Vietnam should carefully review the incentive
structure so that these investments do not go into inefficient
capital-intensive industrial sectors, the ADB said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
