<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Competition to Rise in Thailand's Auto Sales in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's automobile sales in
1998 will be a buyers' market as sales are expected to drop
drastically, according to industry experts.
</P>
<P>
The Automotive Industry Club of Thailand forecast that auto
sales in the country in 1998 could be around 200,000 units,
compared with about 360,000 units in 1997, the Nation newspaper
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The total auto sales in the country soared to 589,000 units in
1996, the highest in the country's history.
</P>
<P>
As a result of steep declines in the baht's value and consumer
purchasing power, fierce competition is expected in 1998 from
manufacturers, who will be fighting hard to keep their market
shares and to compete against used cars, club officials said.
</P>
<P>
To promote their sales, auto companies will try to absorb their
losses, offering more reasonable prices, longer warranty periods
and easy payment conditions and providing better service.
</P>
<P>
In the last quarter of 1997, nearly all vehicle assemblers in
the country reduced their production, either operating at half
capacity or closing down temporarily.
</P>
<P>
It would take several years for the industry to get back to its
size in 1997, the Nation quoted auto industry experts as saying.
</P>
</TEXT>
