<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ramos Orders Energy Chief to Prevent Blackout </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel Ramos
directed Energy Secretary Francisco Viray on Monday to take
measures to prevent a recurrence of the weekend blackout.
</P>
<P>
He also ordered National Power Corporation President Guido
Delgado "to review, reinforce and improve the overall Luzon grid
system and all other systems countrywide" to prevent potential
blackout, a news release from the Presidential Palace said.
</P>
<P>
The 11-hour blackout which hit most parts of Luzon Island,
including Metro Manila, on Saturday afternoon, kept millions of
homes in darkness during the New Year holidays.
</P>
<P>
In his updated report to the president, Delgado said a full
investigation of the blackout is going on.
</P>
<P>
He said that at around 1:28 p.m. last Saturday, an insulator
bolt of a 115-kv electric pole along the Binan-San Pedro, Laguna
transmission line near Metro Manila was damaged, causing fire and
a short circuit on the line and this "initiated the first major
disturbance."
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Press Secretary Hector Villanueva dismissed as
baseless claims by opposition quarters that the power outage was
part of a dress rehearsal for a declaration of a state of national
emergency leading to the cancellation of presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
The united opposition has accused the Ramos administration of
stage-managing the blackout to pave the way for Ramos' stay in
power beyond June 1998.
</P>
<P>
Villanueva said the blackout was caused by a technical problem
and politics had nothing to do with it.  
</P>
</TEXT>
