<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-05 09:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Attack Aims at Wrecking Iraq-Jordan Ties: Diplomat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, January 5 (Xinhua) -- An Iraqi diplomat who survived an
assassination attempt here Saturday has said the attack was aimed
at wrecking the ties between Jordan and Iraq, the semi-official
Jordan Times newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
"They do not want our relations with Jordan to get better or
smoother," Iraqi Commercial Counselor Abdul Rahim Taher told the
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
He further laid blames on "either the Iraqi oppositions or
Israel or the United States" for carrying out the shooting at him
and his 14-year-old son.
</P>
<P>
A gunman in a passing car fired a shot with a silencer-equipped
pistol at the 45-year-old diplomat and his son while he was
starting his car in front of his house Saturday morning. The
bullet hit the car but both of them were unharmed .
</P>
<P>
The car with the attacker then sped away. The diplomat said he
had noticed the same car following him last Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Ambassador to Jordan Nouri Al Weiss has said the
assassination attempt was carried out "by some elements who do not
want to see any rapprochement in relations between Jordan and Iraq
taking place."
</P>
<P>
"There are some parties who are unhappy because the ties
between Jordan and Iraq have started to return to normal. They are
trying to fish in troubled waters," the ambassador added.
</P>
<P>
Jordan's acting Minister of State for Information Affairs
Nasser Lawzi said Saturday that Jordan is very concerned about the
attack and that the police are investigating the incident.
</P>
<P>
Tensions mounted in bilateral relations after Iraq executed
four Jordanians in December on charges of smuggling car parts into
Iraq. Jordan expelled seven Iraqi diplomats in retaliation.
</P>
<P>
But there have been improvements since Iraq agreed to renew an
agreement to supply oil to Jordan at favorable prices. 
</P>
</TEXT>
