<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Shares Close Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong stocks slumped to a
lower close Monday, partly haunted by regional currencies crashing
to record lows and sliding share prices in Tokyo, analysts here
said.
</P>
<P>
The key Hang Seng Index lost 377.03 points, or 3.5 percent, to
close at 10,303.54.
</P>
<P>
The turnover amounted to 5,122.62 million Hong Kong dollars
(658.43 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The index opened at 10,673.91 points in the morning, down 6.66
points, or 0.06 percent, and lost 246.84 points, or 2.3 percent,
to close at 10,433.73 at midday.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong stocks fell 42.19 points, or 0.39 percent to close at
10,680.57 Friday, the first trading day in the new year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980105.0155 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SADC Member States' Growth Rate to Be Up: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 5 (Xinhua) -- The Southern African
Development Community (SADC) is posed to record average growth of
between four and five percent in 1998, save for new members
Seychelles and the Democratic Republic of Congo, a local
economist predicted recently.
</P>
<P>
Kenneth Kotelo, economist at the Pretoria-based Africa
Institute, warned however that growth levels in certain SADC
states including Zambia, could come in a at lower rate.
</P>
<P>
Namibia, Botswana and Mauritius looked set to score rates of
about five percent this year, while the growths in Swaziland,
Zimbabwe and Malawi could come in at Between 3.8 and four
percent.
</P>
<P>
Zambia's growth could be less than the SADC average, maybe at
two percent, and this could be exacerbated if the political
situation in Lusaka worsened in the coming months, Kotelo said.
</P>
<P>
Kotelo was also pessimistic about Angola, saying that business
links in the oil industry were too poor for the country to
exploit fully its oil wealth.
</P>
<P>
The World In 1988, a recently published outlook by the
London-based The Economist Group, forecast a 3.2 percent growth
rate for South Africa, and warned that high real interest rates
would undermine investment and private consumption.
</P>
<P>
The publication's prediction for Zimbabwe is 3.1 percent,
accompanied by a warning that the "preferment process will stifle
growth and undermine efforts to diversify the economy from its
reliance on primary commodities".
</P>
<P>
Kaire Mbuende, the SADC's executive secretary, said recently
that the SADC economies would expand at a rate of six percent in
1998, following the previous year's trend during which member
states achieved positive growth rates of between two and 13
percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
