<DOCNO> XIE19980105.0156 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-05 08:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 200 Illegal Migrants Detained in Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, January 5 (Xinhua) -- A total of 200 foreign nationals
were detained late Sunday night by Turkish police in Istanbul as
they attempted to illegally emigrate to European countries, the
semi-official Anatolia News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
Anatolia said the police staged the operations at 22:00 local
time and those foreign nationals caught included Pakistanis,
Syrians, Afghans and Bengaleses.
</P>
<P>
In response to a letter from his Italian counterpart Lamberto
Dini on the latest fleeing wave of Turkish nationals to Italy,
Turkish Foreign Minister Ismail Cem on Sunday said that his
country is ready to cooperate with Italy to combat the illegal
trend.
</P>
<P>
Cem said the current problem is a case of illegal human
smuggling which is an "extremely serious form of organized crime."
</P>
<P>
"This criminal activity is based on the exploitation of the
understandable desire to have a better life," Cem said, adding
that Turkey has consistently sought multilateral cooperation
against all forms of organized crime and international terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Cem pointed out: "We are taking all measures needed to stem
illegal immigration as an organized crime, through or from
Turkey."
</P>
<P>
On Saturday, 18 unemployed migrants, aged between 20 and
25, were discovered without proper exit permits in a truck
loaded with tires at Istanbul's Haydarpasa port.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that they intended to travel by ferry across
the Mediterranean to Italy, before applying for asylum in
Germany. Each had paid about 1,100 U.S. dollars to the organizers
of the trip.
</P>
<P>
The flood of migrants to Italy started in the past week when
some 1,000 refugees, mainly Iraqi and Turkish Kurds, arrived in
southern Italy, causing tensions in relations between Ankara and
Rome.
</P>
<P>
Around 2,000 Kurdish refugees had arrived in Italy's Adriatic
coast since September. 
</P>
</TEXT>
