<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Religious Conflicts Dangerous, Tanzanian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian President
Benjamin Mkapa has urged people of different religions to avoid
conflicts, otherwise the consequences will be dangerous, press
reports said today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the ceremony to mark the centenary celebrations of
the Western Diocese of the Moravian Church in the Tabora Region,
the president reiterated that people who speak against other
religions will be punished according to the law.
</P>
<P>
The Tanzanians have long lived peacefully irrespective of
their creeds, Mkapa said, adding that religious conflicts are
dangerous and in some parts of the world people were killing each
other because of differences in religious beliefs.
</P>
<P>
Of late, some people have been distributing cassettes,
booklets and convening meetings in which other religions are
disparaged, the president said.
</P>
<P>
Those who are doing this are infringing upon the freedom and
constitutional rights of others, he said.
</P>
<P>
It is the government's duty to protect religious rights of
individuals and ensure that such rights are not violated, the
president told bishops from other denominations and government
and political leaders on the occasion.
</P>
<P>
A total of 80 percent of people in Tanzania are Christians and
Muslims, with the rest holding indigenous beliefs.
</P>
<P>
The president called on all religious leaders to foster love
and peace in the society, and praised religious organizations for
their contribution to the undertakings of education, water supply
and health.
</P>
<P>
On the same occasion, Bishop Isack Nichodemus of the Moravian
Church donated 100 bags of maize as relief food to Mwakabasa
villagers in Nzega District. The village is engulfed by floods
which have isolated it from other areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
