<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Why Kenyans Choose Moi Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Having won about 2.46 million
or 40.12 percent of the total votes cast by a big majority,
incumbent Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi is to be sworn in
today to continue his 19-year-old rule till 2002.
</P>
<P>
All major independent polling observer organizations have
admitted that the "results do on the whole reflect the wishes of
the Kenyan voters and should be accepted in total."
</P>
<P>
As the last of Africa's "Big Men," it seems Moi holds some
trump cards which have made common Kenyans believe he is their
best choice no matter what challenges the country is facing ahead
of a new millennium.
</P>
<P>
One of Moi's key trump cards should be his least tribal color.
He is the only one who has collected more than 25 percent of the
votes in five of the country's eight provinces -- a "must"
requirement by Kenya's laws for a qualified head of state.
</P>
<P>
His closest challenger, Democratic Party's Chairman Mwai
Kibaki, who is from Kenya's most populous tribe of Kikuyu, met
the 25-percent-rule in three provinces while other three big
rivals only made it in their respective tribe's home province.
</P>
<P>
Tribalism has been surging especially since 1992 when
multi-party politics was introduced in the country with 42
tribes. Moi then bowed reluctantly to pressure from home and
abroad to implement multi-party democracy while bitterly blaming
it for what he perceives to be a hotbed of tribalism, violence
and other social evils.
</P>
<P>
Moi himself, a member of the Tugen sub-group of the minority
Kalenjin ethnic confederation, has for years pursued policies of
supporting small tribes and making them allies, together with his
famous Nyayo philosophy -- peace, love and unity.
</P>
<P>
The 73-year-old Moi, who holds the record as the longest
serving president, vice president and member of parliament in the
history of Kenya, also owes his success to his rich political
experiences, local analysts say.
</P>
<P>
"Moi is like a giraffe, while others are like ordinary small
animals. When they are busy grazing down there, the giraffe is
seeing very far," said late Jaramogi Oginda Odinga, the first
vice president and Father of Kenya's opposition.
</P>
<P>
In the middle of last year, he timely and swiftly softened his
original hard tune on constitutional reforms for which the
opposition sought by organizing nationwide strikes and rallies.
</P>
<P>
As a result of his sudden change, parliamentary members from
both the ruling Kenya African National Union and the Opposition
had worked out the constitution reform bills and passed them
through as enacted laws.
</P>
<P>
The move not only to a great extent enhanced democracy and
reduced the then mounting violence and tension nationwide, but
also persuaded many Kenyans of Moi's sincerity for his commitment
to social changes.
</P>
<P>
To the satisfaction of his fellow people, Moi has pledged, in
his final term, to improve government efficiency, remove
corruption, attract more foreign investment, further adjust
economic structure, promote privatization, create more jobs,
develop education and etc.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the sharp division among the opposition, whose 14
presidential candidates stood basically on their respective
tribal line, has given Moi a great advantage by making votes
against him dispersed.
</P>
<P>
Opposition leaders had made repeated attempts throughout 1997
to churn out their common presidential candidate to defeat Moi,
but the efforts ended in vain due to their different tribal
interests and personal ambitions.
</P>
<P>
Moi's success is also attributed to his image as a prominent
peace-broker and ardent advocate of regional cooperation in the
Great Lakes region and eastern Africa. None of his rivals can be
his match in this regard.
</P>
<P>
"I will vote for Moi because he loves peace," said a nurse
working for a private clinic in Nairobi on the eve of the
elections.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, Moi sponsored several regional summits to mediate
conflicts in the former Zaire and southern Sudan. As chairman of
the seven-member Inter-Governmental Authority of Development, he
has played a key role in re-opening peace talks between the
Sudanese warring sides after a three-year deadlock.
</P>
<P>
Election fever is fading fast, but tough challenges still
remain. Can the helmsman bring about a more brilliant future for
his people by whom he has been chosen again?
</P>
<P>
No matter what follows, it is quite clear that "Moi has made
his own footprints in the sands of time," said former British
Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher during her visit to Kenya in
1988. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980105.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-05 07:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia to Sell Gas to Israel Via Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Russia is planning to sell
natural gas to Israel through Turkey, local newspaper Daily News
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Russian Ambassador in Turkey Vadim Kuznetsov told the paper
that the natural gas will be transported to Israel through the
planned Black Sea pipeline between Turkey and Russia.
</P>
<P>
"It was mentioned not only during the recent visit of Prime
Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin to Ankara, but also when Israeli
Prime Minister Benjamin Netenyahu visited Moscow," Kuznetsov
said.
</P>
<P>
He added that Canadian and Israeli companies would be involved
in the construction of the pipeline but failed to mention when the
project will be completed.
</P>
<P>
The Russian ambassador, however, admitted that the main user
of the Russian gas will be Turkey because Turkey is an
energy-starving country.
</P>
<P>
At present, Turkey purchases about 6 billion cubic meters of
natural gas from Russia per year, but the figure is estimated to
increase to 30 billion cubic meters following the construction of
the Black Sea pipeline. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
