<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe to Improve Park Management </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, January 5 (Xinhua) -- The Department of National Parks
and Wild Life Management of Zimbabwe will start a 1.3 billion
Zimbabwe Dollars (80 million U.S. dollars) project this year to
improve the operations of the country' 11 major parks, The Herald
daily reported today.
</P>
<P>
The project, to be extended for over six years, will help the
government reduce expenditure and try new approaches to deliver
services in more cost effective ways.
</P>
<P>
The parks rehabilitation and conservation project will be
implemented with assistance from the World Bank, International
Development Agency, the Global Environmental Fund and U.N.
development program.
</P>
<P>
Chales Chipato, secretary for mines, environment and tourism,
said the desire to improve operations of the parks led to the
establishment of the Parks and Wild Life Conservation Fund to
manage the parks and wild life estate as a commercial entity.
</P>
<P>
The project, he said, aims at improving and enhancing
decision-making by management, assessing skills and training
needs and establishing a performance and evaluation review
system.
</P>
<P>
Elements of national parks infrastructure would also be
improved which are essential to the management of parks for
wildlife and habitat conservation and for sustainable commercial
development.
</P>
<P>
These will include the improvement of roads, water supply,
electricity, communication, staff houses, offices and provision
of equipment, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
