<HEADLINE> E. Africa to Set up Business Arbitration Center </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Kenya, Tanzania and Uganda are
scheduled to set up the East African Business Dispute Settlement
Center to meet the needs of growing regional trade and
investment, the East African reported today.
</P>
<P>
The weekly newspaper said the three member countries of the
East African Co-operation had agreed on the structure of the
business dispute arbitration body at an experts' meeting held
recently in Arusha, northern Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
Once it is set up, the paper quoted participants of the
meeting as saying that it would no longer be necessary for
parties to take recourse to international arbitration.
</P>
<P>
The decision to set up the center came at a time when there is
growing trade and investment within the east African region.
</P>
<P>
Experts at the meeting predict that disputes are bound to
occur, hence the need for an arbitration center.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, experts have recommended the harmonization of
national laws and the introduction of United Nations Commission
on International Trade Law model law on arbitration and
conciliation.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania and Uganda were required to update their laws on
arbitration by July this year as they have outdated laws which
are still subject to courts of law.
</P>
<P>
If approved in its current form, the center will have
international jurisdiction and comprise seven arbitrators, one of
whom would be chairman, and each member state will nominate two
people qualified for appointment to the center as arbitrators.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
