<HEADLINE> Shanghai to Reshape Industrial Structure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, January 5 (Xinhua) -- China's largest trade and
financial center will start a new round of changes in its
industrial structure in 1998 to increase competitiveness
internationally, according to Mayor Xu Kuangdi.
</P>
<P>
The city will take steps to develop financial and information
services, and high-tech industries, Jiang Guangyu, deputy
secretary general of the municipal government says.
</P>
<P>
By the year 2000, the output value of financial services will
go from the present 12 percent to 14 percent of the city's GDP;
while that of high-tech industries, from 14 percent to 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
Information services will also grow 180 percent within three
years.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai will also build two large enterprise complexes, each
with annual sales of more than 100 billion yuan, and 10 enterprise
groups, each with annual sales of more than 10 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai started adjusting its industrial structure in the late
1980s and its economy has been growing at an annual rate of 13
percent since 1992.
</P>
<P>
The adjustments will pave the way for economic growth, says
Yuan Enzhen, director of the Economic Research Institute of the
Shanghai Academy of Social Sciences. 
</P>
</TEXT>
