<HEADLINE> Chinese Rescue Center Successful in Wildlife Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, January 5 (Xinhua) -- A wildlife rescue center in
China's Shaanxi Province has saved more than 120 animals that are
under state protection.
</P>
<P>
The center, which was established in 1987 at the Louguantai
State Forest Park, has rescued 13 giant pandas, 41 golden monkeys,
24 takins, five white-lipped deer, and one spotted leopard, all of
which are classed as grade-one animals under protection.
</P>
<P>
A number of the rare animals have been returned to nature after
having been nursed back to good health, but some are still living
at the center, according to one official there.
</P>
<P>
The center has been studying the breeding of rare animals, and
researchers' efforts have allowed it to successfully breed 15
golden monkeys, one giant panda, and a takin. It has also gained
valuable experience in the rescue and care of wildlife, after
nearly a decade of work. 
</P>
</TEXT>
