<HEADLINE> China's Five Special Economic Zones' Thriving (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 5 (Xinhua) -- China's five special economic
zones (SEZs) maintained their economic growth last year, providing
a solid foundation for next century's development.
</P>
<P>
The economy in Shenzhen, Guangdong Province grew a great deal
with a GDP of 113 billion yuan, an increase of 16 percent over the
previous year, and the city's revenues came to 14 billion yuan, up
6.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
Shenzhen used its advantage of being on the frontier of the
country's opening up by increasing economic and trade cooperation
with the outside world. It estimates use of foreign funds last
year at 2.8 billion US dollars, up 15.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
Exports also went up rapidly, and relations with neighboring
Hong Kong were stronger after Hong Kong's return to China in
July. Shenzhen continued state-owned enterprise reforms last year
in keeping with the 15th Party Congress, and total industrial
output value for last year is expected to be 125.5 billion yuan, a
17.5 percent increase.
</P>
<P>
Zhuhai also in Guangdong has had large infrastructure
projects. Work on the railway to Guangzhou has started, a highway
to Beijing is under construction, and the Zhuhai Airport is open.
</P>
<P>
There were 301 new contracts involving foreign funds in the
first 11 months of last year, with contractual investment
totalling 2.46 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
A modern transport system has emphasized the regional
advantages of Shantou also in Guangdong, where there were 26
berths for ships of more than 5,000 DWT by the end of the year,
including 8 for ships of 10,000 DWT, giving an annual handling
capacity of 21.12 million tons.
</P>
<P>
The city has 44 domestic and international flights from its
airport, which ranks 11th in China in passager handling capacity.
</P>
<P>
Its program-controlled telephone capacity is 778,100
lines, and there is one mobile phone for every ten persons.
</P>
<P>
There were 12,522 contracts worth 5.1 billion US dollars in
foreign funds. Exports were worth 3.03 billion US dollars and
imports, 2.18 billion US dollars, up 84.3 percent and 30.2 percent
over the same previous year period, respectively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
