<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwaiti Juvenile Crimes Drop in 1997: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Juvenile crimes in Kuwait
dropped by 12.5 percent in 1997 as a result of strict
implementation of anti-crime laws and preventive measures.
</P>
<P>
According to the Sunday newspaper here today, director of the
Juvenile Care Department of the Ministry of Social Affairs and
Labor, Nasser Al-Ammar, said there were 2,752 juvenile crimes
during the year as compared to 3,146 in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The rate of crimes committed by teenagers had been on the rise
since the Gulf War in 1991, and this was the first-time decrease
in six years.
</P>
<P>
He said a committee was formed last year to fill loopholes in
the Juvenile Law in light of new social developments in the
country after the Gulf War in 1991.
</P>
<P>
Besides, he said, his department had organized a preventive
program aimed at minimizing juvenile delinquency. The first
quarter of 1998 will witness the implementation of the
department's second preventive program, he added.
</P>
<P>
Juvenile delinquency has been a serious social problem in the
country and attracted great attention and raised serious concern
among the people over the past few years.
</P>
<P>
Experts cited negative effect of various media means, inability
to keep pace with the swift changes in the economic and social
fields, negligence of family as well as consequences of the Gulf
War. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
