<HEADLINE> China Continues To Increase Foreign Exchange Controls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Sources at China's State
Administration of Exchange Control (SAEC) say the country will
increase foreign exchange controls to protect financial stability.
</P>
<P>
Since reforms began in 1994, a system of current account
convertibility was established to eliminate restrictions on
transactions, and China has fairly large foreign exchange reserves
and a stable yuan.
</P>
<P>
For the past three years the People's Bank of China and the
SAEC have done country-wide inspections and exchange control
officials began to see that supervision should be increased
further when they found that some enterprises, individuals, and
international speculators were involved in illegal exchange and
securities activities.
</P>
<P>
SAEC sources say they have closely cooperated with other
departments to focus their investigation on large cases and to
deal strictly with law-breakers.
</P>
<P>
For the past few years, exchange controls have included more
advanced technical measures to allow the early exposure of
abnormal practices, and the system is being connected by computer
to major banks for transmission of information.
</P>
<P>
Exchange control departments have also increased cooperation
with Customs offices. In mid-1997, the SAEC and the General
Administration of Customs signed a memorandum on cracking down on
exchange fraud that involves the use of false declaration forms.
</P>
<P>
SAEC officials say that organizations involved in illegal
activities will face severe penalties and will be subject to
stricter supervision in the future. Those who break the law will
be referred to public security departments for investigation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
