<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Makes Progress in Rural Infrastructure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, January 5 (Xinhua) -- The present Bangladeshi government
has constructed some 22,000 kilometers of metalled roads and 2,600
bridges and developed 300 bazars in the rural areas since its
formation one and a half years ago, the national news agency BSS
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Since June 1996, 34,936 different types of tubewells have been
sunk and over 200,000 sanitary latrines distributed in the rural
areas in a national sanitation program.
</P>
<P>
The government has also launched a 3.2 billion-taka (about 70
million U.S. dollars) micro-credit distribution program among the
rural poor, emphasizing the rural women community for
self-employment and uplift of their socio-economic status.
</P>
<P>
"the government wants to create dynamism in the rural economy
by increasing the purchasing capacity of the rural people" through
rural infrastructure development, Zillur Rahman, minister of Local
Government Rural Development and Cooperatives, was quoted as
saying on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The national economic uplift would not be possible without
making the rule people self-reliant, the minister stressed.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh is an agriculture-based country with over 80 percent
of its 124.3 million people living in the countryside.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
