<HEADLINE> 743 Die on S. African Roads Since Start of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 5 (Xinhua) -- At least 743 people have
been killed in traffic accidents in South Africa since the
beginning of the festive season, the "Arrive Alive" road safety
campaign said today.
</P>
<P>
South African Press Association quoted the campaign as saying
that there had been 534 fatal collisions in which 177 drivers,
249 pedestrians and 317 passengers had died.
</P>
<P>
Traffic flow on major routes around the country ranged from
moderate to extremely busy at the weekend as holiday makers began
return journeys to their homes after the Christmas and new year
break.
</P>
<P>
The nationwide road safety campaign launched in October 1997
has significantly reduced the number of deaths and saved the
nation about 20 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Last year, more than 1,240 people died on roads in the Christmas
and New Year holiday season. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
