<HEADLINE> Severino Appointed as New ASEAN Secretary-General </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Rodolfo C. Severino of the
Philippines officially assumed here Monday the post of
secretary-general of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations
(ASEAN) for the five years from 1998 to 2002.
</P>
<P>
At a ceremony for the transfer of office held at the ASEAN
Secretariat, Severino took over from Ajit Singh, who had completed
his term.
</P>
<P>
The ceremony was also attended by Indonesian Foreign Minister
Ali Alatas, ambassadors from the ASEAN member countries and ASEAN
dialogue partners such as China, India and Russia and diplomats
and government officials from other countries.
</P>
<P>
Severino has carved for himself a distinguished career in
diplomacy, performing various capacities in the Department of
Foreign Affairs of the Republic of the Philippines and foreign
service.
</P>
<P>
As a holder of a post-graduate degree in international studies
from the Johns Hopkins School of Advanced International Studies,
Severino served as third, second and first secretary in the
Philippines Embassy in Washington from 1967 to 1974. He was
involved in the normalization of relations between the Philippines
and China and served as charge d'affairs of the Philippine Embassy
in Beijing from 1976 to 1978.
</P>
<P>
From 1992 to 1997, Severino was the undersecretary of foreign
affairs for policy, overseeing ASEAN-related matters.
</P>
<P>
The appointment of Severino was recommended by the 30th ASEAN
Ministerial Meeting in Kuala Lumpur in July 1997 and approved by
the ASEAN heads of government.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN now groups Brunei, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia, Myanmar,
the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
