<DOCNO> XIE19980105.0188 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Differences Not Barriers, Says Kyrgyz President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA-ATA, January 4 (Xinhua) -- Kyrgyz President Askar Akayev
said different attitudes toward the integration of the
Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS) should not become
obstacles in cooperation between the CIS countries.
</P>
<P>
Akayev was quoted by the newspaper, Slovo Kyrgyzstana (Word of
Kyrgyzstan), on Saturday. He said the different attitudes toward
the integration process resulted from different situations facing
the countries in their transitional periods.
</P>
<P>
He said the CIS firstly denoted an economic association, which
should be conducted on an equal footing.
</P>
<P>
Every country in the four-state customs union (Kyrgyzstan,
Kazakhstan, Russia and Belarus) faced two questions, the president
said.
</P>
<P>
One is the establishment of an open space for the free flow of
commodities, capital and labor forces inside the four states. The
other is the creation of conditions for the integration of the
countries into the open world economic system.
</P>
<P>
Akayev was critical of the imposition of high transit duties by
the customs union states on the Kyrgyzstan-exported goods, which
he deemed was squeezing Kyrgyzstan out of the CIS and the customs
union market.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of the domestic situation, Akayev said Kyrgyzstan
first achieved a stable macro-economy and steady economic growth
inside the CIS.
</P>
<P>
Kyrgyzstan enjoyed a growth rate of more than 8 percent in
gross national product (GNP) in 1997, with very low inflation. The
total output in agriculture grew by 8.9 percent. The country is
now preparing for a new economic take-off. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
