<DOCNO> XIE19980105.0189 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> External Factors Limit Thailand's Exports: Deputy PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's export performance in
the first 10 months of 1997 showed that the country gained limited
export opportunities from the Thai currency's effective
devaluation, according to the Nation newspaper Monday.
</P>
<P>
Thai exporters did not benefit from the baht's float since July
2 as much as they had originally expected, because several other
Asian currencies have also depreciated.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's exports in the said 10 months rose only 19.8 percent
in baht terms, as compared to an almost 50 percent depreciation of
the baht against the U.S. dollar. As a result, Thai exports rose
by only 4.4 percent in dollar terms in the 10 months.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Prime Minister Supachai Panitchpakdi, who is
concurrently the commerce minister, attributed the sluggish export
performance to regional competition, as Thailand's ASEAN
neighbors, such as Indonesia, Malaysia and the Philippines, also
depreciated their currencies and exported cheaper goods to the
world market, the Nation quotes him as saying.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's farm exports will also face fewer opportunities in
South Korea because of its domestic economic turmoil.
</P>
<P>
Supachai believed that the competitive currency depreciation is
likely to spur a protectionist trend in the United States, which
is the most important export market for most Asian countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
