<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India's Industry for Stable Government After Poll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, January 5 (Xinhua) -- India's industry is for a
stable government after the general elections to be held from
February 16, the local press reported.
</P>
<P>
Leading industrialists believe that single party majority rule
at the Center would do a lot of good to the country's economy, The
Hindustan Times said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Most of those who talked to the paper were, however, clear
about one thing -- only the majority party or partner in the
coalition should lead the government and as far as possible the
system of "outside support" should be avoided as it gave immense
authority to the outside supporter without the accompanying
responsibility.
</P>
<P>
Industry representatives were also honest about the
impossibility of the economy reviving very fast. In fact, one of
them said "1998 is not going to be a picnic," the paper said.
</P>
<P>
"What we need today is political stability, end of uncertainty
and restoration of business," said L. M. Thapar, manager of BILT
Company.
</P>
<P>
"I sincerely hope that a stable government will emerge, either
a single party government or a coalition government led by
majority party without outside support. Such a government will
bring about much needed psychological change and help in greater
flow of investment both domestic and foreign," he said.
</P>
<P>
"People are fed up with continued political instability. This
has done immense harm to the country," another industrialist
Kulwant Rai said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
