<HEADLINE> LTTE Member Confesses Attacks on Sri Lankan Sanctuary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, January 5 (Xinhua) -- The attacks on the Yala Wildlife
Sanctuary in Southern Sri Lanka last year were carried out under
the instruction of a leader of the Liberation Tigers of Tamil
Eelam (LTTE), a captured LTTE cadre has confessed to police.
</P>
<P>
Police said Monday that the LTTE activist who was arrested in
Batticaloa, Eastern province, has confessed that he was ordered by
an LTTE leader, identified as Mahesan, to destroy all government
properties within the sanctuary park.
</P>
<P>
He was hand-picked for the job because he is familiar with this
area and fluent in the Sinhala language, police quoted him as
saying.
</P>
<P>
He led a group of 24 armed rebels to enter the jungle park for
their first raid.
</P>
<P>
On their way they came across three Sinhala villagers, who
showed the attackers the jungle paths and gave them information
about bungalows in the park.
</P>
<P>
In return, the villagers were given 3,000 Rupees (50 U.S.
dollars) and a deer killed by the rebels in the park.
</P>
<P>
The rebels used the information to launch their second attack
on the park, police said.
</P>
<P>
However, police said the arrested activist could not provide
relevant dates of the attacks.
</P>
<P>
Yala, one of the key sanctuaries in Sri Lanka, was closed for
several months last year due to security reasons.
</P>
<P>
Many bungalows were burnt, vans were hijacked and workers and
villagers were killed in the park last year. Almost all the
attacks were blamed on the LTTE.  
</P>
</TEXT>
