<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian FM Urges Balance in Immigration Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, January 4 (Xinhua) -- The right balance must be found to
resolve the immigration problem, especially in the light of waves
of Kurdish refugees, Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini said
in Florence Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Dini said the problem was "extremely delicate" because it
involved humanitarian aspects to which Italy must remain highly
sensitive.
</P>
<P>
The Italian government's position is to grant asylum, as it has
done to those claiming refugee status on the grounds of political
persecution. At the same time, Rome is stepping up its controls
along its land borders and coastlines, he said.
</P>
<P>
"We must take into account that Italy is part of the Schengen
system and, therefore, we also have a duty towards the countries
of northern Europe where most of these refugees plan to settle."
</P>
<P>
Italian Prime Minister Romano Prodi, Dini and Interior Minister
Giorgio Napolitano were to meet Sunday evening in Rome to discuss
the problem.
</P>
<P>
Referring to Germany criticisms, Dini said he did not think
Germany blamed his country. Germany knew it also had a constant
and illegal flow of immigration that originated at Germany's
eastern border.
</P>
<P>
"Italy, because of its geographical position, is the most
exposed to this assault." He said it was harder to maintain border
controls at sea than on land. In any case, the minister felt
confident that Italy could count on the full understanding of its
partners. 
</P>
</TEXT>
