<HEADLINE> Most Thai People Spend Less: Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANBKOK, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Most Thai people were spending
less during the past six months because of the economic crunch,
according to a survey published Monday.
</P>
<P>
About 74 percent of the 5,914 people interviewed nationwide in
December by Suan Dusit Rajabhat Institute said they had tightened
their belt to cope with the economic downturn.
</P>
<P>
A total 3,052 people, or 51.6 percent, said they did not have
enough to live on and were in debt, while 2,452 respondents, or
41.5 percent, said they could just about make ends meet and did
not have anything left to save.
</P>
<P>
Only 410 people (or 6.9 percent) surveyed said they could
manage to save some money, after the Thai currency was floated on
July 2 last year.
</P>
<P>
About 22.66 percent of the people interviewed said they had
sought extra jobs during the latter half of last year.
</P>
<P>
Up to December 31, 1997, the baht lost 83.35 percent of its
value against the U.S. dollar. The reference rate for that day was
47.286 baht to the dollar, as compared to 25.79 on the day prior
to the float. 
</P>
</TEXT>
