<HEADLINE> China Buys Record Number Of Aircraft </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 5 (Xinhua) -- China's civil aviation industry
ordered 97 aircraft from European and American manufacturers in
1997, according to China's Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic
Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Government purchases made up the bulk of these, ordering 50
aircraft from Boeing and 30 from Europe's Airbus, but private
airlines have broken new ground in aircraft purchases. The Yuanda
Group of southern China ordered a six-place business aircraft and
a Bell-208 helicopter from abroad. China also purchased five
passenger aircraft from Russia.
</P>
<P>
The European manufacturer AIR increased its role in the China
market when ten of its AIR-72 passenger aircraft were ordered,
thanks to persistent efforts over the past decade.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, airlines managed by the Civil Aviation Administration
of China (CAAC) got six MD-90s, two Boeing 747-400s,
eight Boeing 737-300s, two Boeing 737-200s, three Boeing 737s, two
Boeing 777-200s, one Boeing 757, one Boeing 767-300, 12 Airbus
A320-200s, five A340-300s, two A320s, and two AIR-72s. 
