<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Austrian Exports to Eastern Europe Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, January 4 (Xinhua) -- Austria's exports to Eastern
Europe and developing countries rose 25 percent in 1997, making a
major contribution to its rising exports growth.
</P>
<P>
Jan Stankovsky, an expert on exports in the Vienna Institute
for Economic Research (VIER), told Die Presse daily that Austria's
exports to Eastern Europe accounted for 17 percent of the
country's total exports in 1997, a remarkable increase over the 10
percent of 1996.
</P>
<P>
Austria's exports to the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries, Latin America and China also gained upward momentum.
</P>
<P>
However, exports to Southeast Asia were still not encouraging
in 1997, he said.
</P>
<P>
Although exports to the European Union, the biggest trading
partner of Austria, increased by 10.7 percent in 1997, its
percentage in the total dropped from 68 percent of 1996 to 63
percent of 1997, he said.
</P>
<P>
Another development in 1997 was the 20 percent increase of the
exports of high value-added products.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to those changes, the total volume of Austria's exports
in the first nine months of 1997 increased by 16.3 percent, the
highest in 20 years, he said.
</P>
<P>
Experts from the VIER predicted economic growth of Austria in
1997 would exceed the expected 1.6 percent, and in 1998 was likely
to climb to 2.5 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
