<HEADLINE> Poppy Plantations in Northern Thailand Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Poppy growing in northern
Thailand's province of Mae Hong Son is on the increase after years
of gradually reducing plantation sizes, according to a local press
report Monday.
</P>
<P>
In 1987-88 there were 10,737 rai (1,718 hectares) of poppy
plantations. In 1994-95 this had been cut to 1,543 rai (246
hectares). But recent figures say the size has grown to 2,611 rai
(417 hectares), making the province the country's biggest poppy
producer.
</P>
<P>
A drug intelligence officer in Mae Hong Son was quoted as
saying that the crops were grown in steep valleys in the
province's Pai district and Pang Ma Pha sub-district which are
almost inaccessible to the authorities seeking to destroy poppy.
</P>
<P>
The crop is then supplied to heroin production plants along the
Myanmar border.
</P>
<P>
Opium, heroin and amphetamines were the top three illicit drugs
produced on the Mae Hong Son border.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
