<HEADLINE> Italian Premier Says Kurdish Exodus Needs EU Help </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, January 4 (Xinhua) -- Italian Prime Minister Romano Prodi
said Sunday that European cooperation is needed to help deal with
a flood of Kurdish refugees.
</P>
<P>
More than 1,200 people, many of them Kurds, arrived in Italy
last week seeking asylum. Some 1,300 more are believed to be on
their way.
</P>
<P>
Over recent years, Turkey's southeast has become a bitter
battleground between government forces and militant Kurdish
separatists who are fighting for an independent Kurdish state.
</P>
<P>
On the Italian offer of political asylum for the Kurdish
refugees, most of them from Turkey, Prodi said such status will be
granted to those who are worthy of it.
</P>
<P>
"The right to asylum is granted on an individual basis, and not
collectively. This is a very firm position because there is a
common line among all the European countries," the Italian prime
minister said.
</P>
<P>
Prodi told reporters: "Italy considers Turkey a country not
only of strategic importance but also essential in the framework
of political relations for peace in the Mediterranean."
</P>
<P>
Some European countries worry that the immigration problem will
soon become theirs and accused Italy of being soft on the
Kurds. But Prodi said a common European policy was needed because
it was such a large-scale phenomenon and individual countries
could not cope effectively on their own.
</P>
<P>
The Italian prime minister said that cooperation among the EU
states was necessary. 
</P>
</TEXT>
