<HEADLINE> Promising Mining Industry in Tibet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Southwest China's Tibet Autonomous
Region will launch broader cooperation with domestic and foreign
counterparts in the mining industry, in a bid to speed up the
development of the local mining industry, according to the regional
government.
</P>
<P>
The region is going to develop its mining industry by using
government investments and introducing domestic and foreign
investments, expertise and trained people.
</P>
<P>
Tibet has found 96 kinds of mineral deposits, with the proven
reserves of seven ore deposits among the top five in the country.
</P>
<P>
However, low management level and backward technologies have
slowed down the development of the local mining industry.
</P>
<P>
The region now has 220 mining enterprises, with the combined
output value only standing at 170 million yuan in 1996. These
enterprises now mine only 22 kinds of mineral deposits.
</P>
<P>
Sources from the regional government said that the region will
focus on the production of electrolytic copper, and the mining of
chromium, gold, lead, zinc and silver in the period from now to
the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The annual output value of the region's mining industry is
planned to increase at an average rate of 20.8 percent in the
coming three years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
