<DOCNO> XIE19980105.0214 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ho Chi Minh City Plans Economic Rejuvenation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, January 4 (Xinhua) -- Ho Chi Minh City, Vietnam's
largest economic hub, has set up an action plan to re-organize the
banking system.
</P>
<P>
The Vietnam news agency (VNA) reported Sunday that the plan, a
part of a programme to promote investment and develop state-run
industries, also involved strengthening co-ordination with the
State Bank of Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
The agency said renovation of the financial and banking system
is one of the five major economic and social tasks in the city's
development plan for 1998, which will also focus on the city's 18
commercial joint-stock banks to improve the efficiency and health
of credit activities.
</P>
<P>
A senior official of Ho Chi Minh City was quoted by VNA as
saying that banking staff should receive further training to meet
the continuing market-oriented economy. The official claimed the
public now had more than 1.2 billion U.S. dollars in home savings,
which the banking sector could mobilize for production and
business development projects.
</P>
<P>
To improve the investment environment, city authorities will
focus on administrative reforms, introduce incentive policies
involving tax concessions, land rental reforms and infrastructure
projects to attract foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
The city hoped that more foreign direct investment projects
would begin in 1998, involving industrial production and
processing industries for export goods to help boost the city's
economy.
</P>
<P>
Domestic investment would also be encouraged, with loans being
allocated to enterprises for upgrading technology to compete with
imported goods, while priority policies on taxes, capital and
simplifying procedures would also be introduced.
</P>
<P>
Ho Chi Minh city recorded a 12.1 percent growth in gross
domestic product (GDP), or 3.1 percent over the national level in
1997. Its industrial value jumped by 13.7 per cent as against
13.2 percent for the whole country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
