<DOCNO> XIE19980105.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Plans to Develop Three Hi-Tech Industries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai, the largest
industrial metropolis in China, plans to boost three hi-tech
industries in the coming few years, according to local government
sources.
</P>
<P>
Three hi-tech sectors -- information technology, biological
pharmaceutical and new materials -- will help increase the city's
output value of high-tech industries to 170 billion yuan by the
year 2000, up 100 billion on 1996.
</P>
<P>
Hi-tech industries accounted for a mere two percent of the
city's total industrial output value in 1992, with the figure
rising to 14 percent 1997, and even further to 20 percent by the
year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The development of hi-tech industries will help develop the
city's six pillar industries -- automobiles, household electric
appliances, petrochemicals, iron and steel, and power
generation equipment.
</P>
<P>
Hi-tech products currently account for only five percent of the
city's total exports, with the figure expected to hit 15 percent
by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Local officials note that the development of hi-tech industries
has contributed greatly to the city's economy which has grown by
14 percent annually over the past five years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
