<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine International Reserves Decrease </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 5 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' gross
international reserves dropped 23 percent to 9 billion US dollars
as of the end of 1997 from a high of 11.7 billion dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The country's monetary authorities are now looking for ways to
beef up and rebuild the dwindling dollar reserves, local press
Monday quoted Central Bank Governor Gabriel Singson as saying.
</P>
<P>
The central bank, Singson said, gives priority to raising
additional financing from commercial and official sources to
further bolster international reserves.
</P>
<P>
Singson said the central bank was seriously considering the
issuance or floatation of 500 million dollars worth of bonds with
maturity ranging from five to ten years.
</P>
<P>
In fact, negotiations with several banks to raise the initial
money are already ongoing, Singson said.
</P>
<P>
On top of this, Singson said official money from multilateral
sources such as the International Monetary Fund (IMF) and the
Japan Export-Import Bank (Jexim) bank is forthcoming.
</P>
<P>
By the end of this month or early next month, the Philippines
would be able to draw from the IMF and Jexim bank some 640 million
dollars worth of financing tied to the country's compliance of the
commitments under the IMF's Extended Fund Facility, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
