<HEADLINE> U.S. Balloonist Slows Pace over Black Sea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 4 (Xinhua) -- U.S. balloonist Steve Fossett
today floated his "Solo Spirit" balloon across Bulgaria and over
the western edge of the Black Sea at a slow pace, his mission team
at St. Louis said.
</P>
<P>
At 5:20 a.m. CST (1120 GMT), Fossett was heading south at 25
mph (38 kph) at an altitude of 22,000 feet (3,625 meters). His
mission team at Washington University in St. Louis projected that
Fossett would pick up winds flowing eastward at a more rapid clip,
sending the balloon over the southern edge of the Black Sea and
into Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Fossett, on his fourth day mission to circle the globe without
stop, told his base headquarters that if he was unable to get to
the upper air jet stream, he could drift into Russia, which would
not be ideal.
</P>
<P>
The 53-year-old adventurer launched his balloon from a sports
stadium in St. Louis at 5:04 p.m. CST (2304 GMT) on Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980105.0224 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Balloonist Meets Equipment Malfunctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 4 (Xinhua) -- U.S. balloonist Steve
Fossett's mission to pilot a balloon to circle the globe without
stop was in jeopardy today as his heaters were malfunctioning.
</P>
<P>
The 53-year-old adventurer was shivering in his cockpit and it
was very unlikely he would complete his trip, Alan Blount, mission
control director, told a news conference at mission control base
in St. Louis on Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The announcement came after Fossett's two vital heaters went
out and he appeared to be headed toward the north side of the
Black Sea over Russia.
</P>
<P>
Blount said there was "serious discussion" Sunday morning
between the mission control team and Fossett about executing a
landing, because "the wind track at that time showed that
eventually he would begin to loop back to the northwest toward
Murmansk and Moscow."
</P>
<P>
The team believes Fossett could continue traveling eastward,
rather than looping north, which would put over the very southern
tip of Russia. He may still attempt to break his 1997 record of
traveling 10,361 miles (17,434 kilometers) in a balloon.
</P>
<P>
"If you set a record, that's great, it's a milestone," Blount
said. "If you get all the way around the world, that's the pot of
gold."
</P>
<P>
At 3 p.m. EST (2000 GMT), Fossett was 225 miles (360
kilometers) northeast of Istanbul, Turkey, riding the wind toward
the east at 26 mph (42 kilometers) at an altitude of 23,000 feet
(3,625 meters).
</P>
<P>
The team reported that a heater was malfunctioning in Fossett's
6-by-4 passenger capsule beneath the balloon and the temperature
had dropped. Meanwhile, one of the two propane burners that are
fired whenever the hot air balloon must be heated for extra lift,
was not working properly.
</P>
<P>
Fossett took off from St. Louis on Wednesday and hoped to
complete his flight in 15 days. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980105.0225 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Adheres to Strict Monetary Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 5 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine Central Bank has
vowed to adhere to stringent monetary policy in 1998 as
uncertainty in the financial market due to a depreciating currency
continues to hound the country.
</P>
<P>
"There should be no short-term compromises on monetary
discipline," central bank governor Gabriel Singson said in his
year-end report and economic outlook for 1998 to President Fidel
Ramos.
</P>
<P>
Singson admitted that the "early months of 1998 are likely to
continue to be difficult for the economy especially as the
regional financial crisis continues," local newspaper Manila
Bulletin reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
With this as premise, Singson said the monetary authorities'
actions would appropriately "focus" on price stability as well as
stringent monetary discipline.
</P>
<P>
Apart from prudent monetary policy, Singson believed that the
attainment of a sound overall macroeconomic situation for 1998
"requires a strong fiscal position to ensure reasonable economic
growth prospects with price and balance of payments stability."
</P>
<P>
He described the year just past as "very tough and challenging"
with the ability of the monetary authorities challenged by the
currency crisis and high interest rates.
</P>
<P>
But despite the generally difficult regional conditions,
Singson reported that the Philippines has stood its ground and was
"able to avoid worse outcomes" such as those seen in Thailand,
Indonesia and Korea.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine peso, Singson said, has depreciated by only 56.2
percent against the U.S. dollar. In contrast, the Indonesian
rupiah dropped by 141.7 percent, Korean won by 101.2 percent and
the Thai baht by 87.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, Singson reported, that the Philippines'
financial system has remained relatively unscathed while the three
countries are facing deeper structural problems especially in
their financial sectors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
