<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Hopes Levy to Retrieve Resignation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 4 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu today hoped that Foreign Minister David Levy
would retrieve his resignation decision.
</P>
<P>
In response to Levy's resignation announcement made this
afternoon, Netanyahu said in a press conference here that he
regretted very much when he heard about Levy's intention to leave
the coalition government, adding that "I hope he will change his
mind."
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu said that he had made great efforts to implement the
commitments he made to Levy and he will continue to consult with
the Treasury to meet Levy's demands.
</P>
<P>
He noted that despite a total of 15 billion shekels (about 430
million U.S. dollars) overdraw inherited from the previous Labor
government, the Likud government has managed to allocate
considerable resources to development towns and disadvantaged
neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
Giving his reasons for resignation, Levy said the proposed
1998 state budget does not address the country's social and
economic problems, particularly the sufferings of the low income
families and these people really needed for support.
</P>
<P>
He criticized the government for ignoring the promises made to
him last Summer in formulating the the state budget and for
lacking the positive intention in moving the Middle East peace
process forward.
</P>
<P>
In his agreement reached last Summer with the government,
Netanyahu promised to allocate about 100 million U.S. dollars as
special budget for Levy's Gesher (bridge) Party to address the
problems of development towns and underprivileged neighborhoods
in the 1998 state budget.
</P>
<P>
Levy also said that another reason for his resignation is that
many cabinet members did not support his policy of resuming peace
talks with the Palestinians, particularly the implementation of
the Hebron Agreement with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
But Netanyahu said today that only the current coalition
government is capable of achieving the peace with security,
stressing that "we are striving for a permanent final settlement
with secure arrangements ...and we can live here in a secure state
for many many years."
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu also noted that he is confident that despite Levy's
resignation his coalition government will continue leading the
country. He said that "I believe this coalition will continue,
its work will continue, and its existence will continue to do
what it has to do until 2000."
</P>
<P>
Under the law, Levy's resignation would come into effect 48
hours after his resignation letter to the prime minister. So the
prime minister still has two days to persuade him to change his
mind. But it seems that Levy would be unlikely to go back as he
had made very harsh criticisms of the government.
</P>
<P>
With the resignation of Levy from the government, Netanyahu
only enjoys a marginal majority of 61 seats in the 120-member
parliament. Levy's Gesher Party has five seats in the
parliament in which Netanyahu has escaped narrowly several
no-confidence motions in the past several months.
</P>
<P>
The main opposition the Labor Party has already announced that
it would make another no-confidence motion in the parliament
against Netanyahu next week. If the Labor succeeds in winning the
motion, elections would be held within two months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
