<DOCNO> XIE19980105.0234 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-04 21:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey, Israel to Hold More Maneuvers in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, January 4 (Xinhua) -- Turkey and Israel are planning to
hold more joint maneuvers in the Mediterranean in an effort to
enhance their coordination, the Anatolia News Agency said today.
</P>
<P>
Senior officials from the Turkish General Staff, who spoke on
condition of anonymity, were quoted as saying that Turkish and
Israeli military officials are to discuss the details of the
exercises in the coming months.
</P>
<P>
They said that the naval exercises involving Turkey, Israel and
the United States, which are scheduled to start on January 5, have
been code-named "Reliant Mermaid I."
</P>
<P>
The three-way exercises, which have been postponed several
times, prompted harsh criticism from Iran and the Arab countries,
which accuse Ankara of forming military alliance with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has been trying to play down the significance of the
joint exercises, describing them as "a routine search-and-rescue
operation."
</P>
<P>
Two frigates, one helicopter along with 800 sailors from the
Turkish Navy are to participate in the upcoming maneuvers,
military sources said.
</P>
<P>
One destroyer and one helicopter from the United States and
two Israeli warships will be involved in the long-expected naval
war games.
</P>
<P>
Jordan announced Sunday that it would take part in the
Turkish-Israeli-U.S. maneuvers as an observer.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, which has also received an invitation to send observers,
refused to attend the disputed war games apparently due to fears
that its image in the Arab would be damaged if it was involved in
the maneuvers.
</P>
<P>
The quickly growing Turco-Israeli military cooperation has
aroused uneasiness among the Arab countries, which termed Turkey's
move as a betrayal of the interests of the Muslim world.
</P>
<P>
Turkey, however, has repeatedly stated that the Turkish-Israeli
military cooperation is not directed against any third country,
saying that such a cooperation is aimed at promoting peace and
stability in the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
