<DOCNO> XIE19980105.0235 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: More Americans Go Hungry due to Food Stamp Cuts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 4 (Xinhua) -- Four months after the last of
27 billion dollars in food-stamp cuts took effect in the United
States, evidence is mounting of a large increase in the number of
people who can't get enough to eat without help.
</P>
<P>
Charity leaders and experts on hunger believe the cuts are at
least partly to blame, according to an Associated Press report
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"The economy is booming by most standards we use to measure it,
and yet we're saying our demand is up," says Sister Christine
Vladimiroff, a Benedictine nun who runs Chicago-based Second
Harvest, the nation's largest charity to getting food to the poor.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Conference of Mayors released a survey last month that
reported average 1997 increases of 16 percent in requests for
emergency food -- the largest jump in the 29-city survey since
1992.
</P>
<P>
The study found that 19 percent of those seeking help were
turned away, and 46 percent of the cities reported that charities
and other private programs provided inadequate amounts of food to
those helped.
</P>
<P>
Forty-four percent of city officials cited cuts in the
food-stamp program as a chief cause of the problem.
</P>
<P>
But many said the blame cannot be placed solely on the changes
in the food-stamp program, which reduced the stamps' value,
limited to three months the eligibility of able-bodied, childless
adults and denied benefits to most legal immigrants. Other,
perhaps larger, factors include unemployment and low-paying jobs,
they said.
</P>
<P>
Second Harvest supplies through a network of food banks more
than a billion pounds of food a year to the hungry, elderly and
the downtrodden. In an informal survey, Second Harvest found it
took an average of 14 percent more food to feed the hungry this
November than last.
</P>
<P>
Thirteen states have moved to keep food-stamp benefits intact
for some legal immigrants by spending their own money.
</P>
<P>
Second Harvest and groups including the National Council of La
Raza, the Jewish Federation and Catholic Charities are lobbying to
get President Bill Clinton to push in his January 27 State of the
Union address for renewed access for legal immigrants. They want
him to include the same stipulation in his 1999 spending plan to
be unveiled February 2. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
